\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid16413182 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You are Ralph Gray of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}102 Bradfield Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Stretford{\*\xmlclose}, and you were born 1839 at Urmston. And your father was called Otto Rudolph Graffinghof. That was your name. You told me about going into the Army and changing your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 But he came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and he got national - naturalized. Not nationalised. That was our name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Gra}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 ffinghof}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 ?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And you shortened it to Gray?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. Well it was during the first war. I don't know whether you - are old enough to remember it, I don't think so. No, only - there was such a lot of bitterness against Germans. And I was in the cotton trade.
 And I knew when they came back from - from the Army, and the war was over, I guessed there'd be such a lot of bitterness, I had - and I had to go round trying to sell yarn to different firms. Well when you had in your business card with - Otto Rudolph Gr
affinghof on it - well there - there'd be just no straight away. And I - I was put into a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 battalion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
, 31st Middlesex that nearly all were in the same position as I, that they had a German father, or mother, something like that you see. Because - they - t
hey said that if any of such people were captured they'd be shot as traitors. From - they had deserted {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. So we had a special - you know, special regiment, all - all like I. Well while I was there I changed my name legally. Yes. To Ralph - I got - go
t - chose Ralph for Rudolph and Gray. Ralph - yes, Ralph Gray. So - whereas I became Ralph Gray. Yes. Now ask me how old's my father, I don't know. He - he left before my mind started functioning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When he went in a mental home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Railway Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, Urmston. It was a larger house because were getting - getting more of us. And he was taken ill there with cerebral disease. About 1898. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You were about nine years old when he went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. So we moved to - when he went we moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}G
reenhayes Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - in Moss Side. Am I - am I going to fast or - he died, yes, he died in 1900.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And then you moved to Brook Bar?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We moved to - that was - that was later than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In 1904?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Of course that was - like the Warehouseman and 
Clerks Orphan school then, I don't know if you knew that. It was, yes. Warehousemen and Clerks Orphan school. And it was a very good school. Yes. And they got me in there. And - I was there from - nine 'til fifteen, age you see. And - it was in - after we
 left there - the - that we moved to Brooks Bar. I had left school then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You say it was a better locality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Aye. Moved to Brooks Bar - about 1904. A better locality you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You had four sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I had four sisters and no brothers. About one and a half years between. Two girls, then me, then two - two more girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Your father was born in Germany, can you tell me his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh his - father's occupation. Well he was an agent - in the paper trade. He was an agent for it for paper, on his own account.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did he have an other job before after he became that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
He didn't, no. Oh no, I - before or after - well I don't know what his job was before he came to England of course. But - you see I - I saw very little of him, I did
n't - I hardly knew him. There's only about two incidents - that I remember with his presence. One is where he - he put a - overmantel up over the mantelpiece with a German - German Eagle on it in a transfer. That was the only thing I remember. And then -
 
the next thing I remember is - Christmas and Easter. At Christmas we - all the children were brought down in their nightgowns into the dining room to open their parcels. But I don't remember what was in them of course. And at Easter - with - they had the 
- coloured Easter eggs, all dyed. And they were hidden amongst the trees in the garden. And we had to go out and find them. That's all I remember about my father, because - after - very soon after he went away, I was sent to Cheadle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7943465\charrsid8081393  H}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 ulme school. It was a b
oarding school you see. So I - I only came home in the summer and the Christmas. So really for all that - those years, I - I didn't know much about - what the family was doing or anything. So I really didn't start living at home until I was fifteen. Anywa
y I don't know whether that helps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't know - well she was forty-three in 1912. That's 18 - 89 to 19 - from 1912.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 She died in 1912?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, she died at forty-three. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did she come from? Well she - she was a Manchester person. But I don't know where she came in the first place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Had she any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 She was a barmaid. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did she work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did she work - after - no, no. NO, she was too busy having - employer bothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many rooms were in the house at Brooks Bar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well of course - yes - well that was after - in Brooks Bar, that would be after I was fifteen, you see. Well I had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many rooms were there in the house at Brooks Bar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh you're talking about when I left school. I've got down here. Six rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did anyone else besides your parents, brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, we - we had a lodger. Yes.
 A male lodger. I think I put him down. Yes, one lodger. I think he was a very old friend of the family. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother have anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, but not - not - not living in. Just had the - a casual worker came in during the day. And - and that's all I - all I know about that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh was done at home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your father or mother mend or make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No, she didn't make the clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were the clothes new or secondhand?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - my mother was - very - very hard up then because she was a widow you see and. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 I think - well in fact I'm almost sure, she got an allowance - from the German family From my - I had two uncles - you see the family a 
girl - there were two sons, yes, two sons in Germany - my uncles and - I think it was - the one we knew mostly, Herman, he also came to England. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
But he didn't get naturalized, he worked at Ashton Brothers the cotton, big cotton firm. Well he must have made
 an allowance, to mother, with out me knowing, oh well - of course we were too young to be told anything about it. But I know that - she did get - a - a small allowance. And that's one - but I think she, you know, couldn't manage very well on it I suppose
 
and one thing why she had the lodger I expect. But - but most of the clothes we got - of course I - I, while I was at school we had - we had uniforms, school uniform you see, that was provided. Being an orphan it was all provided. But then the - the other
s
 - I don't remember how they - when I came home on holiday they simply just got their clothes on, I didn't know where they'd come from, I didn't ask anything. But afterwards - when we're working, well then we're in the Provident Club. You've heard of that
 
- yes. I think we got most of the things from there. But - I know - in my case - with the lodger being there, he was very tall chap and they were - his clothes was acceptable to being - small - small - ensmalled as you might call it you see. So I came in 
t
o a lot of those. And I - I know I do remember specially when these tight trousers that men are wearing now, they think it's a new fashion, but it was all fashionable then. I mean they were wide well they were narrowed down and all the bad parts cut out a
nd I had them in - and that was my new suit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't know about - I can't answer that. As I say, I didn't know - know him so long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did he dress or undress or bath you or read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh yes, I - I think so because - he was very domesticated and - yes. And from what mother said he thought the world of us all. And did his best for us. Well I - I - I believe that because of the Christmas and Easter - you see, so - that would be so.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any tasks to carry out regularly at home to you're your mother and father? And how long did you do them for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - I don't know that we had special tasks, we - we seemed to just - when I was there seemed to do what was 
necessary. But of course mother always did all the cooking, yes. We had good meals - always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the older children help the younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I know I always lit the fire in the morning. That was my first - my job. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the older children help the younger ones?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, they - they took their turn. Of course we made our own beds. And - and I can't think else. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Daisy went away didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 She - she left and - and I had - we had - I had an uncle, you know, the - there 
was those two brothers. Well he lived in Milburn Road. He had one daughter. And - I never knew his wife, well in fact I never knew him hardly then, but - apparently she was lonely and the elder - my - elder sister used to go there and keep her company Pla
y
 with her and that. And then ultimately she went to stay there altogether. She went to live at Milburn Road - with them, and he brought the two girls up together. And then - when he retired he went back to Germany, took her with him. And of course she bec
ame a German entirely. She married a German military officer, a military doctor he was, married there and of course she is a German now. She'd eight-five I think, something like that. But then - and of course she's a widow. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, the children - the children helped each other. In various ways.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I 
- I don't remember until I went to - I got to school really, and then - well all had, at the - at the Cheadle Hulme - 'course we all had to go and put ourselves to bed. We had to march up there at definite times for everything you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Tell me about school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
It was a - it was - it was rally a - I think it was founded by - I don't know who they were but they were warehousemen and clerks and some association. And they founded the school - it was a lovely school, well built and then of course it was 
right in the heart of the country, Cheadle Hulme were miles away from anywhere. But - I suppose now it's all built up, I don't - I've never been for years. But - the - they give us a very good education. Although they were very strict with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 At - at nine years old, when I got - when I went there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 But when you first went to school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When I first to school - I - I don't know - that would be - that would be after we'd gone to Greenhays. I 
went to school in Denmark Road but I remember very little about it. There - there was - that would be - I suppose I'd be seven or eight years old. But I don't know if I went before then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Starting afternoon school? I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What time did you start afternoon school? What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
You mean the earlier one than this? Oh just an ordinary - I don't know what kind they called it, I don't know, it were a church school. I think it was a church school. Christ Church, in Denmark Road, Moss Side, then - or Greenhays they called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I just walked there, it wasn't far from where we were living then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 My - next sister - next younger sis
ter. She came with me then, we went together. And she ultimately got to Cheadle Hulme as well. And just - the older - not - not the eldest, the eldest girl had gone to Germany. So if I call the eldest, she - and she and the youngest were left at home with
 mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did you have your midday meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well that - that - that is before Cheadle Hulme? Well we had it at home, we came home for it because - it was only just a walk - home. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you 
think of school? Oh well, I never knew much about it, I - all I remember about that school is that when we were out playing the school outside, there's tall window sills had got all ridges in that - because where we used to sharpen our pencils and - made 
channels on it. That's all I remember about Christchurch school. I may have written them down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You were nine when you first went to Cheadle Hulme?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 That would be before Cheadle Hulme when I first went. Then - nine years old when I went to Cheadle Hulme.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 It was a boarding school was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What kind of school was it. Boarding school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Except the first week after going back from holidays. I used to cry hard then because I was sorry. But - after that we
 had - enjoyed it very much. It was a - joint school. I liked the teachers. But - some of them were - well, some were very strict. Yes. And I remember one particularly. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 
Her name was Miss Bourne and she was very, very strict. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And - everybody was frightened 
to death of her. Because she was so strict with them you see, and - they didn't like her at all. And I know they chose monitors of course for various jobs, and - and I - I got the job of - of going round to the teachers studies, they had a private room ea
c
h you see, to go around filling the ink wells with ink, once a week. Well when I got to Mrs Bourne's room - I - I knocked at the door and walked in and of course I got met with a volley - to - go outside. Get out, you know all that sort of thing. Next tim
e you come - knock at the door and wait for me to say, come in. Of course I thought it was - polite to knock at the door and walk in. So of course that was the first thing, and then after that - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  I went I did something wrong with the ink, I either
 filled it too full or not full enough or - when she said something sharp - I - jump like that and spill the ink. But anyway, what - what I was going to say - we had - a friend of mine and myself, I suppose we were very naughty really, we were young crimi
n
als I expect, but we used to get up at night and go raiding the larder. Because this - they kept a very deep drawer full to the top of raisins, and things like that, and candied peel. Well of course we used to go and have a nice handful of those. And - we
 
were - one day when we was - I was in the - in the lavatory, they had wash hand place, we had a big - washing place with bowls all round, just divided by a low partition. And we were behind this partition and I was talk - talking to another friend of mine
 and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 offering}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 him a bit of candied peel. But - I didn't know that one of the teachers were on the other side of the wall. And reported the fact that - we were handing candied peel out and of course I was called to the study and - I got a long lecture, and w
hile he was lecturing he was getting his cane out of the drawer - then, I want to know who was with you. Who helped you? I said, no, I was by myself sir. Which of course - which wasn't true, he knew very well a boy wouldn't go by himself all that way. But
 
anyway I held out, because - one of the chief codes of the school was you never give a - never tell any tales to anybody. If - if anybody was caught telling a tale, they got the whole - and the scholars were behind him when they came out of school, they a
ll marched behind him - shouting at him, I don't know where the name came from but they called him a clat. If you tell a - tell tale you were a clat. Well they used to follow him, clat, clat, clat, clat. That }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 lasted }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 for a week or two. So I suppose nobody da
red - dared give anybody away. And that was the only reason, I was afraid of that, it wasn't for any courage or that at all. But anyway I - I didn't tell him. And I got extra caning for that. Well - next time I went with the ink pots - Miss Bourne was nea
rly like a mother to me. I expected her to start cuddling and kissing me, the way she went on. And she got a - a big slice of cake and put in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 my}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  pocket. After that she made a real fuss. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 She wasn't strict anymore?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - not with me, yes. T
he dining room, the - the tables were set like that round in - and the teachers were along that end. And there's one of the scholars who sit on the end table told me afterwards he'd heard - heard Miss Bourne talking to the other teachers and - quite eulog
ising this - this boy that had - you know, that wouldn't tell a story. And then that's one - one thing that I remember about her. That nobody liked Miss Bourne, only Otto.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, like manners or tidiness or punctuality or ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. I think so. Manners, they taught manners. Yes, and tidiness of course we had to be tidy. Then of course punctuality didn't come in because it would have been rather - we lived there you see. We'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 always}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 be there. And - the ways of speaking, oh aye, we learnt to speak properly. And - I don't know about - the school manners because - I mean table manners, because there wasn't much chance. We had - we just had a - a barrel shaped mug. When we - we marched
 into the dining room and it was all set out with a mug in each place, where we sat. Because we were always in the same place. That was full of tea. And - two big - plates of bread and butter About that thick. And very thick pieces. And that was all we ha
d for tea. So - we'd no time to show any manners really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
The same - same applied for breakfast. But sometimes we had a plate of porridge. Porridge. And then this bread afterwards. Well they used to just pass the b
read round. And - and some like - another funny thing that they - they did, if you hadn't enough and you could eat another piece - some of them would think, well I could eat another piece, but I - I could only eat half of it, well they used to sign to eac
h other, would you like half a piece of bread, you know, like that now. That - that meant will you have half with me you know. Yes. There was many funny ways. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you have for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 For dinner - the dinner was on the table in the pla
te when you got there. They were very good dinners. And - another peculiar habit they all had - it was supposed to be - infra dig to be fond of potatoes. Amongst the scholars. I don't know why, because I used to enjoy them. But - those that - that - they 
t
hought most about used to wrap them in a newspaper and go and throw them down the lavatory - afterwards. And anybody who used to eat all his potatoes was more or less - of the lower orders. That's another peculiar habit you know, I don't know why it was. 
B
ut anyway we had good dinners. And generally followed by - what they called spotted dog, you know, a suet - a long suet pudding. About that long and there's a monitor at the end of the table, he had to cut it up and serve it. With happen - with - with syr
up and - or sometimes we had prunes, but no custard with 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Meat? Oh yes, that was - that was on the plate when we went. A piece of meat and potatoes and cabbage, whatever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, oh yes, every day. Yes. And - I don't know - well of course at Christmas we didn't know because we'd gone to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 home}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 - we went home then. But it was always more or less the same. But we enjoyed it well enough. And tea - about once a month perhaps we'd have a - a cookery lesso
n for one of the classes, there was just a little bun in each place, when we - only one table at a time. Just a little bun, you could eat it in one mouthful. And - on Saturday, when we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 
marched}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  out of the dining room, 'cos we had to march out - in order, th
ey have a - a box of oranges or a box of apples outside the door. As you - as you walked eat each one you just picked one up and - go. That was one of the luxuries. We were never allowed sweets - or - we weren't allowed to have money at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh the teachers were allowed to use the cane as well then. They could cane us. But if it was anything very serious - they report - send you to the headmaster's study. Well then of course you got - a thicker cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 For what offences?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes, the girls were the same. They met in the classes, but - they weren't mixed in school, they had one at each - at each end of the school, boys and girls. And they - but they mixed - they - they met in 
the classes. But they generally had all the girls at front and the boys at the back. Except on a Sunday - as it Sunday afternoon we were allowed to walk round the grounds. Just - after - go to Sunday school first Then after that they could just stroll rou
n
d the grounds. But not with girls unless they were related. I used to walk with my sister round there. The others, they just walk on their own and - just smile as they passed a girl and that was - but they were treated just the same in class. There no - n
o difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 For what offences were you punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well I don't know, it'd be mostly for talking in class or - or scribbling things when they're not listening you know and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Yes, mother - mother did and she like - liked to know all about it when we got home - from - for holidays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did she ask about what you did at school or visit the school or meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, not - they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 ' ask what w
e did because - really after we'd been for nearly six months - we wouldn't remember what we'd done you see. But - they had special time - they only had occasion when they could visit, they didn't come - couldn't come and see us at the school, but - once e
v
ery year - they brought the school down to Manchester to the Atheneum. They had - yes, it was a - it was a meeting of the committee and - all of the members I suppose. I suppose all the warehousemen and clerks, they would - and - the scholars, we were - w
e
 were in a separate place and they'd been practicing sing - singing a song - a choir, and then of course they rendered this song and they all got the clapping. And the - the whole purpose of it was that those that were leaving at the end of the term, they
 
had to come forward and stand there - in some - while they read out their - the result of their schooling. And - then the - any of the employers in the audience could make offers to give him a job. That was the idea of it you see, but - they'd make notes 
a
nd - and then read all this - all your achievements, then you'd to go back to your place. But then, after that was over, your parents were allowed to mix with them you see, they went in there and had a good long talk with the parents and - and a good feed
 
as well because they always brought a bagful of - something to eat. But they had - and then - the next - another time was - they had a cricket team in the school. And - but they never went playing anywhere. They always played at home. The other teams had 
t
o come to the school. Got a nice cricket - cricket field as well and - but the one exception, Longsight cricket team - was supposed to be a very well known team then, and they came to play at Cheadle Hulme, and once a year they were allowed to - our schoo
l
 was allowed to go and play them, at their own ground. So the whole school went. Then they made a garden party of it. See the - had feeding in a tent and all that sort of thing, and the parents were allowed to come then. There was only those two occasions
 when they could get visiting you. Weren't allowed to come in between term or anything. There was no - no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, no, they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 a mixed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  lot. They were mostly orphans. But 
they had just one or two - there's just one or two who came privately. And their parents paid for them. But - you know, very few of them. And of course we always recognised them because they wore their own clothes. Not the school clothes. But they - but t
h
ey had to have all the same things as ours. Carried on just like us, only that they went home for - you know, at different times. But they - they slept with us and that and stayed in the boarding. But - with 'em all being orphans, some of 'em came from ve
r
y poor homes. And others from - more or less respectable ones. But that was the reason - you were not allowed to have money. You were never allowed to have anything to spend or anything. So that none of us really knew - what type of home the others came f
r
om. And there'd be a good many of them that - very friendly, perhaps one was a - a very poverty stricken and the other one more or less - in a good position. But they didn't know anything and so they - they made friends with each other. And we were all on
 
equal terms. Which was a good idea. But if - if we got any money, sometimes the parents would send - when they wrote to them they'd send a few stamps in letters you see, well - you're supposed to hand that back to the headmaster, he kept an account for yo
u. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Kept - he put it in the bank for you and when - when you went home they give you - what - what was owing to you, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
But you were never allowed anything to spend. And it weren't a lot. Wasn't allowed to have sweets, or things of that kind. All you'd have an orange or apple on Saturdays
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No, they'd no favourites. No. No, they were all treated exactly alike. All had the same opportunities and - everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No special gangs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I think they all - we certainly got groups because they were aged from nine 'til fifteen. But it was age grou
ps seemed to more or less - play together. Because - what amused them didn't amuse the others you see, they - they had their own games and that for playing, like really- and that sort of thing. But my friend and I were very keen on gymnastics. We enjoyed 
that as much as anything. And - the bigger crowd - they weren't allowed to play football. Weren't allowed a football team really. But they were allowed to - to kick a ball }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 about}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  the playground. Only small one, they weren't allowed a football. The only - the only games they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 permitted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
, there was cricket and lacrosse. 'Course - with being a - a lacrosse team, made them feel - above all the rest of the community you see, because it's supposed to be a - it was supposed to be a - a high class game. Well it wa
s. Well they - the - the lacrosse team were allowed to play outside the school. The only thing that they would allow, but the cricket team were never allowed to go out. But - anyway they had good sports at the school. But - as I say they - for that big - 
kicking about they - they all mixed up and - boys about that big'd know that and - and there was no goal or anything, they just run about kicking it to the one spot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I were fifteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Would you have stayed longer if you had had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well there was no chance, you never - never allowed to. Except - I think there were two occasions that two of 'em wanted to become a teacher. And they stayed on as pupil teachers. But - that's the only - only 
occasion I remember. We weren't allowed - to have - extra education there or anything like that. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you attend any part time education afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Any regrets? No, I don't think
 so. I was quite satisfied, we - we seemed to get - a - just an inkling of everything, but we - of course I never qualified specially in any subject. But - I enjoyed a bit - a bit of French and a bit of Shakespeare and a- geography, and that, but what I w
a
s chiefly - noted for, I did very good drawing. And I got - for the - perspective drawing I got into that. And I was allowed to go and show all the other boys how to do it. But I couldn't do it now for the life of me, I've forgot all about it because - wh
en I left school I - I got put into - cotton trade, when I - when I should have been put into some drawing office really but - I didn't know anything about that. So of course now - that part of me education was neglected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you think you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 benefited}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Benefited}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 from attending - oh yes. Oh yes, I think so. I couldn't say really I - what way. But I think - what I knew of all the other children there, they were - they were made into like - I should say, decent citizens. Because we
 were all - we were taught to - to respect each other and then of course this - clat system made us all not to be - against each other. And - and as I say we had - just a - a - enough of an inkling of every subject - just enough to give you a chance of ch
o
osing one for - for a career if you wished. You see. It would - if we'd only been - clever enough to think it over we could have - gone through it to see which we liked best. But I didn't - I didn't try to think, only as I liked drawing. But I never knew 
that you could do - earn a living at drawing. The only thing we knew was when you leave school is to go to work. And work didn't sound as nice as drawing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means or earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No, they weren't allowed to. They - they daren't leave the school at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well that was - office boy in a yarn agents. That was the first job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 That - th
at was through the school. Yes. They - afterwards - the Secretary of the school had an office in Manchester. And - when we got an offer from - from business people we wrote to the - they write to me and any of the other - they - some of them had found a j
ob straight away with a - I went to one or two of them and they said they'd let me know as usual, but they didn't. But I - ultimately they sent me to this firm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What exactly did you have to do in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - I - I had to - I had to look a
fter the petty cash, which never amounted to more than a pound. And - I had to - post all the letters. All - all the letters that were written came to me. And I had to copy them. In those days, they - they hadn't - they didn't have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 type}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  - a typewriter, not
 in that place. And they had a - a press and a - a big thick book, all the pages were made of - like tissue paper. And they had to - put the letter that was written, it was all written by hand of course, well you put the - you'd to wet the page, and put t
h
e letter on that page - the ink letter, then other sheets on both sides, then you put it in the press and - with it down press it tight. Press it tight, and then - open the book of course and - the letter was copied onto that tissue paper page. And that w
a
s - yes, that's where they kept it. And one of the things I had to avoid is not to wet the page too much, because - after the boss had written the long letter you find it all - all - rolling with ink and water. Have to write it again, well then that meant
 
- a bit of trouble But anyway that was one of the jobs. I had to copy all the letters in that book. And then enter them up in - in the stamp book and put them in envelopes and address them. Then they'd got to - stamp them and - and all that sort of thing,
 and had to go the errands. Then I had to go and - bring the dinners - they sent to a local - caf\'e9, sent for their dinner and you'd bring it on a tray up the street you know and - 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What hours? I had to be there at quarter past eight. Until six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you work Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Sunday, no, not Sunday, no, I used to work Saturday morning, 'til one o'clock. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No pay - we had a weeks holiday but no pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What were you paid, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Five shillings - to start with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you feel that that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I never thought about it really 'cos - most of other office boys seemed to have the same wage. I got about half a crown a - a 
year raise. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
I don't know what it was spent on, it just went into the general household fund. But I got some pocket money back, I forget how much it was, it would be about a shilling I think, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I got on very well. Quite good company.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh he treated us all right, because he was a wo
rk - a working man who'd worked his way up and - got into their own business. They were quite nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He was all right we thought, we liked him. But of course we used to make - jokes about him. One of his - chief habits
 - he could never resist a piece of firewood if he saw it lying about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He used to take it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
If he saw - he used to come home - he used to come back to the office many a time - carrying an odd bit of wood in his hand and - and put it down - yes. W
ell our office were in Cannon Street. And Vale Street was just at - the next street to us. And - there's a - a firm in Brown Street we used to deal with you see and we knew the - we knew the office boy and the clerk there. And - they came and told us once
 
that - that our boss had picked a piece of firewood up from outside their door, you see, and brought it home. So - so we - we thought well - we'll said, we'll have a bit of fun with this. So - they came - they showed us - where it was. So we went and put 
it back again in the same place. And there were - we did that for three or four days on the run. And - putting it back outside their office and he came - came and brought it back. And there we were passing it to each other for a long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was he mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes, well I - I suppose he was mean in that way. Well we didn't know of any other method really, only - he seemed to be reasonable. But - he was very keen of course on profit and - saving things. The - they - well any - if you wanted to say anything
 to them or give any message, of course you had to write a note and put it on their desk. But - one of the jobs that the warehouseman had was to help to open the post. As he opened the post he'd got to rip the envelopes and - and put one - put the blank p
a
rt on a file, and that's what they - the paper. Anyway that's a habit that he - I've kept all along because I just do the same as that. And - any blank piece of paper I just - I - either I stick it in there for writing on, well, I've got that I don't like
 to see a piece of blank paper thrown away, with no writing on it. And that's one way he was mean in that respect and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did he do with the firewood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well they - they lit fires in the office you see. Oh yes. Oh we had fires in the office then, there was no other means - warming them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
I liked it all right but it was - there was not much chance of getting on really. And then I kept - they kept me as the office boy for a long time and I - of course I h
adn't - I suppose I hadn't the gumption to - to try and get something else, although - I did have, they - they said - my mother and all her friends said that I should have been an engineer. Because I used to like to be making models and - and different th
i
ngs at home. Only cutting papers out and that sort of thing. But - of course we - we didn't have nothing to do with - couldn't chance it. But - evidently mentioned it to Uncle Herman, the one where my elder sister was. And - he said - he wrote over and to
l
d them, if - if we didn't like our job, I could find a job we liked and if it was necessary to help he - he'd help. And so when - then they told - they told him that they thought I'd make a good engineer, and of course he said, very well, if you can find 
a job in an engineering works I'll pay }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 a premium}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 for you to be apprenticed to them. Well - oh now - after that - I had - bilious attacks every other week - diplomatic ones you see, while I went looking after a job. And - I went to every engineering place in
 Manchester that I knew of. All over the place. Asking did they want anybody. They all said no. They gave no reason at all, they all said no, and no, there wasn't - until one - one friend - I don't know the - who she was, but - her husband - worked at -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Hans Reynolds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. And she was friendly with him so she took me with her once to go and visit this chap, he was a manger. We had quite a pleasant evening see and - he was asking all the questions, 'cos I thought he might find me a job. Well he wa
s the first one who told me that it's because you are wearing glasses. At that time they would not allow anybody in an engineering works with glasses. 'Cos they weren't very common then as they are now. Used to call 'em specky four eyes. So - and - it's b
e
cause they were afraid of any damage you see, if anything went wrong, the glasses got broken. Well, of course when I wrote - we wrote and told Uncle Herman the reason he was very annoyed about it. Said, why on earth didn't we tell that we - that I wore gl
asses. Because he didn't know. But - luckily I could write back shortly after and to remind him that he had got a photograph of our family, the four of us, and I'm there wearing glasses. So there's no reason for us to explain it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you do after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
So I - I just stayed where I was. And - yes. And - and - I stayed there - I got into the warehouse after that, I was ultimately the warehouseman, looking after all the goods, loading and re-loading and that. And I - I - got - oh while I was th
ere I - I took on - went to night school to learn book keeping. 'Cos I - I told the boss then that I'd like to learn book keeping, if any opportunity came to go into their - into their office, you know, the cash office, I'd have liked it. So I went to - t
o
 the grammar school to learn book keeping. And - but before I'd finished - the war came. And so I joined up. So I was still belonging to that firm while I was in the Army. But - before I went I - I'd managed to pass the exam for book keeping, so I got the
 
- I'd got the authority then to ask for a book keeping job. Anyway as - when I got back again - the - they'd changed their system and - they'd given up the warehouse and moved into Victoria buildings, just a - as yarn agent so there's no warehouse job. Bu
t
 they offered me a job as a salesman. At thirty shillings a week and commission. That was - I - I had thirty shillings a week. But the commission never materialized because - they were so strict in the - the customers they wanted. Whenever you find a cust
o
mer, say, oh - oh he's a bad payer, we don't like him. So I - I never did very well really. Until they retired. The boss and his brother. They retired - because they did so mighty well in the cotton trade after. You won't know about that I suppose. In bet
w
een the wars. The cotton trade - they went mad nearly. Selling and buying. And - the cotton - and most of the cotton mills were getting refloated like they're doing now with the - other companies. And the people were paying thousands and thousands of poun
d
s to buy the mills. And they were making good profits. Well you can tell, one of - one of our - one of our bosses, they had a few shares in a mill, they paid forty pounds of them, for the share, and somebody came and asked - would they sell those shares. 
They were offered four hundred pounds for the forty pound shares. And that's how it was going on, it was so - so very wealthy, you know, they were wasting their money But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you belong to any trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No. No, no - no trades union then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you feel that there was a division of interest among workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well I - I hadn't started thinking much about it then. I certainly read books and - had Socialist principles but - I didn't realize then that the Socialism is not workable, because of human nature. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers, did you feel that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - yes, I - I'm trying to tell you, everybody should have a training you know, r
emember that. They said - if you were just a clerk you were not much good. But if you had a trade - handicraft, that - that - they were supposed to be most important Like a joiner or - like - all that kind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well, no, I don't think it changed me attitude - in - well I just carry on in the normal way, I - like to keep on working - fell in love and got married and - you know, and brought a family up, and that's how we got on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, I lived at home for - 'til mother died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no - that didn't change at all, no, just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 With brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No, because we all got our own jobs, we were working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well yes, I started - with the - my friend I had at school. I met him again and - he belonged to the 
Methodist church and then he - he prevailed upon me to join as well. That was the first time I'd had anything to do with the church, of course I joined there and - got very interested in it and spent a lot of time there. Socially and otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I didn't take any interest in politics for long you know. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You told me earlier something of how you spent your spare time, did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go out in the evening, and where to and who with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, I gave up - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 had to really leave the school b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 ecause - I went a bit deaf and couldn't follow what was going on. So I - I - then - 'course we had the children to bring up. Then we moved up 
here. So since then I never - never bothered at all. Because - it's no use me going to any service or any meeting because I can't hear what was going on. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When you lived at Brooks Bar what room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh we had the bathroom there - we always had - it was - it was in a bedroom made into a bathroom. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How often did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Every Saturday afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Same day. Every Saturday, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did all the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well always in the kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there any occasions when they ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only on Sunday dinner. We had Sunday dinner in the dining room. That's when -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  was the middle room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
She had a - it was a - well it was then called a scullery. But we had a kitchen range, when the - in the kitchen. With a fire fired oven you know, she did the cooking there. There was no stove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh that was in the kitchen as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
When? Oh as soon as we got up in the morning and - but we each got our own. Mother didn't get up early, she stayed in bed - she couldn't - she was very bad sleeper. And she never used to go to sleep 'til about three o'clock i
n the morning. Used to sleep - used to lie reading a novel - Woman's World and all that sort of thing, dainty novels and goodness knows what. So she - so she never came - she never had any breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What members of the family were present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only
 - only on Sunday were all present. But during the week, each one got up and got their own breakfast and clear - buzzed off to work you see, so - didn't all meet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you usually eat and drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Chiefly bread and jam for breakfast. And tea of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And midday meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
And - midday, we used to take - I used to take - bread and butter in a parcel, and tuppence to buy corned beef. You get two pennyworth of corned beef. But - I got to like bread and butter, and put the tuppence in me 
pocket. Yes. But anyway - after I had done it - I've got it - for eighty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What about evening meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Evening meals, mother always cooked a dinner for us. So when I got home by - when I got home there was always a hot dinner there for me. I 
suppose the others had the same but sometimes they'd have it at different time, got home and had their dinner and gone out you know.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have meat for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Meat? Oh yes. Had - meat several times and - and fish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
I don't remember having tinned meat very often, it seems to be the fresh meat mostly. But - not every day because some days she'd cook fish. My favourite dish was - well I like it now - fish and parsley sauce you know, and - and an
other of my favourites - was - mackerel and mustard sauce. And - it used to great, very nice, but always very hot, the mustard, mix mustard with it, don't now how, but - I used to enjoy it. And sometimes we had nothing but - but haricot beans. Nothing, ju
s
t a big plateful of haricot beans. The big ones you know, we - we liked it very much. And - and of course there was hot pot. You know that - plenty of hot-pot. And she always kept a - stockpot you call it, a big panful of stock, always on the hob. Kept - 
throwing everything into that and - and everything that was left over. I don't mean off your plate but - bits that we didn't want more you know. And that made lovely dinners, pea soup and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. She didn't bother with that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Wine or any medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was there any beer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 brewed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No, we hadn't the garden for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they buy any? Tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh used to buy - I don't - don't remember tinned v
egetables or fruit, we had - she; managed to buy the fresh vegetables. Of course greengrocery was cheap then you know and fruit. The only fruit we had it was always bought. I don't - I don't remember - don't remember seeing any tins about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did - they keep any livestock for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever get any extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Used to buy rabbit but we never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you ever remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No, I don't think so. She used to eat very little in any case. Although she was a - a big - fine woman. I forget how - how heavy she was but she was very heavy. But she used to have - she only had dinner. And she'd no breakfast or tea. Just had her din
ner once a day that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your father have more food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I can't remember - I don't remember what he had, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Yes we all took part in - any conversation that was on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, what was cooked was the only one for everybody. There - there was no variety in the one day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate, what did they say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - I never remember an occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, you could ask for it always, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, if there was any, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, I 
- yes, mother - mother was strict about that. Yes. And - if you put the knife in your mouth - eating peas off a knife and things like that, it was very - that was very infra dig.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I don't know - I
 don't - I don't remember ever doing it, I don't know whether there was a rule against it but - we never seemed to want to do - because we just sit down and have our meal and then get up. We used to - we didn't used to sit and wait 'til everybody had fini
shed. Just get up and - go and do what you wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you always have the same places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We'd have - it was only Sunday - that we did that. Or perhaps at tea, you know, at teatime we'd all sit together, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you always have the same places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. You see, it was only my habit, it wasn't because of - any right at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How was the meal served, who served it? And what order were you served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - don't - there was no special order about that, they just - whoever was there you know, she brought their dinner in to them and - started on it, then the next one came in and got in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did the younger brothers and sisters sit before they could feed themselves, and who fed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - I hardly remember when they were young. But I suppose mother fed them because I know I never helped with it and I don't know whether they ever did. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. She'd tell you that she was easy to talk to wasn't she? She used to like to go to - go and have a - a lie down on an afternoon. On a Sunday afternoon. When we were courting. She - Mrs Gray'd come back to ou
r house and which is in the garden and reading or whatever it was, mother'd be up in bed asleep as far as we know, or we'd be just quietly reading and - perhaps like the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 lavatory}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  brush'd come fluttering down along by us. Or then - you know, a toothbrush an
d - and any kind of thing, throwing down - it was her and she'd got up and there she was flinging things at us from the window. Yes. She was very full of - full of fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If you had any worries could you share them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, you'd - yes, we could always talk to her and - about anything - any - difficulties in anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well she - she expected to treat her - well we did treat her with respect and affection, because - we thought the world of her. All of us.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I had to behave normally, you know - she wouldn't - wouldn't allow any - any quarrelling or anything like th
at. Of course we never had much - to quarrel about really. We seemed to get on well. Only the - the eldest sister. The one that gone away. She was one that was - going her own way a lot and - stayed out - you know stayed out late at night and come - she d
idn't behave as - we - like we did. But even then there was not much - trouble about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - I don't remember that either because - by the time I'd settled at home at fifteen of 
course we were - we weren't fighting with each other. I don't think she said so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be, did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I don't think she didn't mention it specially you know but - she wanted us to grow up respectably. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did your parents think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh they didn't like it. No. And we didn't use it at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If we were there we were allowed to take part in it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen, if you were punished, by whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I - I don't know. I hardly ever remember that - don't remember moth
er disapproving of things, she - she'd say so if she did but I don't think there were any punishments at all. As far as I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You never remember being punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - we all seemed to behave - normally. Sometimes foolishly of course and -
 but I - I can't remember ever getting punished by mother for anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you receive any presents, have anything special to eat or guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well we never bothered with birthdays. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you remember anything you did with your mother on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well I - only what I mentioned at first with me father. But with mother it was always a special day for - for Christmas dinner. But she was very fond of a
 goose. We always had a goose for Christmas. And then - she made a special ceremony of it, and lasted about a couple of hours I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 With - dinner sort of thing you know. Yes. And - and I know she always had a goose. And - after t
hat - a giblet pie for the next day. She always used to save the goose's giblets. Which I never could have fancied. But anyway she made a giblet pie and of course - when the pie was there I couldn't recognise what they were so they enjoyed it. In ignoranc
e.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Oh we had a - we had a piano. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Gladys was learning, that's the - the one who came to Cheadle Hulme with me. She was learning, she - she managed to - fiddle her w
ay through it but - she never - never became a pianist or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - our own what we brought. I - I belonged to the library you know and you see bring library books home. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What about newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, we didn't - they didn't buy newspapers or - or the magazines, all mother's, all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 women\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  magazines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you ever remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, she - as I say, she used to read all night nearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they ever read out loud to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember a funeral in the family and who attended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 mother\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 of course, my mother's funeral. That was the only one. My mother. Mother died, she were only forty-three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was it before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Before - yes, 1912.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me attended and what their clothes were like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, we had - mourn - we were in black mourners clothes. Were just our family. And - I forget, did - did - Aunt Emily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 The German people took charge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. My Uncle Herman. He wrote - he sent to this -
 this relation of his - it's his - his wife's sister to come and see us and look after things. Well then she took charge more or less, 'cos I was only twenty-two I think then. I hadn't much sense by then and - and - anyway she came and took charge and - I
 
- of course it was - I don't know how - about the kids, but I know, he had - in the first place he didn't approve of my father marrying a barmaid. In the first place. And he seemed to always have the impression that she was - a common barmaid, and they th
o
ught every-thing she did was - very low, you know, that sort of thing. And he thought we - we would be all brought up the same. I know they - he had it in - in mind that we were - rather a - ragged looking lot. But he sent - and he sent for her to - to ca
l
l and see us, and to arrange things for us. Once she - she came of course and - she said she'd look after things, and - asked the girls what had they done about clothes. She said, I - all right, I'll get you your - your mourning clothes. And - what about 
y
ou? To me. Well, I said, I - I've already been and ordered a suit. Oh you shouldn't have done that. Shouldn't have done that, that - that's a very - a - a big mistake and - anyway it's all right. But of course I'd paid a lot more than she would have done.
 
But - anyway, she ordered the mourning clothes anyway. She got some very cheap stuff for the two girls. And - I think she came to the funeral, I'm not sure. Then after that she - she arranged things - and she moved us from - Brooks Bar to - Longsight. The
 
place then - they were building houses and they were advertising big letters, Pembertons new houses. Then - so she went to look at them, she said, just the thing for you. They were like - like four matchboxes stuck together, the size of them. Oh they were
 
little tiny things. Anyway she put us there and fixed us up and - she bought lino for the floor. You never saw such cheap lino in your life. Anyway we stayed there for a while and then - we got fed up with it because we - it was uncomfortable and I - I ha
d
 to travel from Longsight to Moss Side for the church, because I still belonged to the church, and - and of course Mrs Gray was then living in Moss Side as well, I had to go down there to do the courting. So we went back to Moss Side. And that - and that 
caused a fall out with her so - that's how it happened. But as regards the funeral - mourning, we all - we all had our mourning clothes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you ever taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations, and with who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, we - no, I didn't do anything. No, we each had our own friends really and - went where we liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Never went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Mother never - mother never went out from home. She - always stayed there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Just on very, very rare occasions - she'd take the younger girl out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 But - for the last few years of her life she never - never left the house. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you never go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No. Not 'til I were married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could you tell me how you spent your Saturdays in those days, and how about Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, well - I spent it with that friend - from - when we go to church. And - spent most Saturday afte
rnoons cycling. We were both got very fond of cycling and we went all over the place. Until teatime. And then I had my bath of course. I needed it after an afternoon cycling because then - they'd just started bringing - with motor cars. We called 'em cart
 
without a horse. And - when they're on the road - you wouldn't see many of them, they - there'd be about one perhaps every half hour and then - the dust they kicked up. When we got back home we just looked as though we'd been in a flour mill. Dust all ove
r
 us, hair and everything. So of course I had a bath then. And then I - after tea of course on Saturday I - I went to - went to see the lady love. We spent the evening walking. Very few yards and you were in the country, then. Alexandra Park was the - the 
country then. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you play games and did your parents think it was wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. They bothered, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents attend a place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go to a Sunday school or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Oh yes, went to Sunday school. Methodist in - Moss Side. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. Oh yes. And - Whit Week. On the Wednesday afternoon - they all went to Alexandra Park - and - and they had - did they take buns and - they ha
d sports and things then on the park. On Thursday - we all went on a lorry. To Ford Lane, Didsbury. Then - we had - of course it was a habit then, a big cart horse and a lorry with - with - the forms from school. Oh we were happy with that. And on Thursda
y
 afternoon. And on Friday we went for a days outing. Either by train, or - it was mostly by train, but those with bicycles of course went on bicycles and we had a - we went to various places like Alderley Edge and all that and - and - and I know we though
t Aldersley Edge was miles away, really enjoyed it. We went to Bollington and different places like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What other social activities organised by the chapel did you take part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Oh yes, they'd all kinds of - we had meetings. We - the Christian Endeavour once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. The Christian Endeavour, they had a - they had a meeting you know like a service. And they all - and they joined the Christian }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Endeavour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  and - they took the pledge to - to do their best to brin
g - bring Christianity and that sort of thing. Had to live a Christian life. Oh it was very - was very pleasant - meeting. It seems to have died out a lot now. But I've got - I've got the badge of it and - that that she bought me. A golden badge with C.E.
 in - on it. That was one.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No I didn't belong to the choir. But they had - had parties.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the chapel have a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, they had - they had a temperance meeting. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you a member?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. Temperance - their activities - they - they just - they held meet - meetings, that was all and - and more or less like a service, but they never - they had people coming to sing and - you know, give - perform - entertainment. That was the - the 
Band of Hope we called it. They -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you belong to any other club organised by the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
They organised a football club but I never bothered with that. But they had a - a harriers club. Cross country running. I went there, went with them. And
 that - we had a happy time then. But one difficulty I remember - coming to the service in the Christian Endeavour service, and then having to change afterwards to go running - across country running. Because we only had a - a cotton vest and white shorts
.
 Anyway I solved the problem - by - of course was - it was - we didn't go in the summer, it was always mostly winter sport that you know to keep warm. And I - I wore me shorts, and I cut a pair of old trousers - cut the legs off a - pair of trousers and p
u
lled them up me legs with - with elastic bands like garters, and kept my over-coat on during the service. And they were - and - and very few of them noticed it but - some - some did and they used to kid me about it you know. So that - where the others wer
e trying to - to find somewhere to change, didn't bother me, I just slipped these off and I was ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was grace said at meals in your family, and by whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We didn't - we never did it at home. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No, we didn't have it at home. But of course we were expected from - from the church it was expected you would do. But not at home, never bothered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother take an interest in politics?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, mother - mother had no politics. No. Well n
obody seemed to bother then, we seemed to have a Government and that was that. It stayed there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - well she used to - I don't know how - mother didn't - she seeme
d to be busy all the time when she was home. But sometimes - she - she was very friendly with neighbours. I know they - they often had the neighbours next door in or - for two or three - and they used to have a musical evening between them. But we never j
oined in, we - we'd be there enjoying it and singing and playing the piano, we'd be in the other room if we wanted or else we'd be off out somewhere you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs, boot, sick or funeral clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their jobs or their house if they voted differently from their employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I didn't - don't remember that, no. The employers never said - never bothered about politics as - as we would 
concern them. No. It never occurred to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 All got on very well together, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was there any one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393  there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 was - the one that came to school with me, Gladys. Well - we're more or less alike in most - in most of our - respect. Then - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 that\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  how I - I found the wife. She was - we all went to the chapel, and she was very friendly with Gladys. And of course she came to the house with Gladys often. And th
en - Gladys - Gladys went then to live with a friend of hers. She left home for a while. So the - Mrs Gray then took on with Di, the younger one, and still kept coming. And then somehow or other - cupid shot at us and - and there we are. And so she was ha
nded on to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 As a child who did you play with, brothers, sisters or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Not - I don't remember playing with any neighbours - I think - I think we just - kept together you know, between ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In the - 
well - it had to be in the house because - while we were children we'd no - no garden or anything. Only in Urmston we had a garden. But - such a short period. And then the other in Greenhays there just had a back yard. Suppose - and - if we did play with 
anybody it was - neighbours in the back entry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 At Brooks Bar where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well at Brooks Bar we had - we had a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  a garden at the back. And - we did play then with - of course only - only - I'd be about - about sixteen or seventeen then. And - we got friendly with the - with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 of the - of the other neighbours. And mind I do remember that the - the - the house was backing onto - big houses in Withington Road. That the backs came to t
he backs of ours. And - and some of them were empty. And of course - they would be got into then and we used to in - playing in there, in those houses. And having a bit of fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, we were allowed to, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 More or less hide and seek, that was about the only thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Well we had - we had to come in and get washed otherwise like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents discourage you from playing with certain children and if so, why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. Never - got to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only the - only the chapel and the - Christian Endeavour and those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you spend your free time when you were at school, did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh at school - the - of course used to have games. You know, like ludo - and draught and that. And they - they built a special room for - fretwork. And of course you don't see much of it now bu
t - they had a nice room for - a lot of the boys got very fond of making fretwork. Making all kinds of models, so they had a - this room built specially, with a long bench, about as long as this room nearly. So as anybody could - could all work along you 
k
now in space. And - there was many nice models - and then the - the headmaster and - lent them some tools - to buy their wood and the tools and everything. And of course they had to - take the money out of the bank that he'd got for them. And that was one
 very - very nice hobby we enjoyed - I made a lot of things in that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go fishing, for walks or bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No, they weren't allowed out of school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I didn't. Only gymnastics. But a lot o
f the other boys did, they played cricket and - lacrosse. But of course they - that was only at weekend, they were allowed to go to the playing field. Otherwise they - just played games in the playground and - maybe kicking a ball about and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go to any theatres or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or music halls while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh after I left school. Yes, went to the grand - the Junction theatre and - threepence in the gods. Oh I remember that, we used to go - it wasn't - wasn't far to walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Not at school we didn't. No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't remember any - how much we had because - you see, I left home so early you know, nine y
ears old. And we never had pocket money at school. And of course after when - when I started work I - I hadn't - I forget even how much then - I think it was only about a shilling a week. Plus those tuppences that I had for dinner you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family, relation or friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - she had a woman used to come in to - when we were at Greenhays, she used to come to help and work a bit. But when we got to Brooks Bar - nobo
dy came, she had nobody to help. Just did it herself. But I don't know whether - what she did because - I can never remember noticing anything being cleaned or polished and - and I don't remember noticing any dust about or anything. So I never know how th
at -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - she - I don't remember her being ill at all. But I know - if there was any need - the girls would - join in and get things ready you know. They could always manage. The girls would look after things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby? And how much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents have friends, and where did you see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only - she had neighbours and - and friendly with all the neighbours. But she'd no special friends that used to come visiting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So they never came visiting to the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh they did so. Yes. Because - there - ther
e's no cinemas or anything. The only - the only thing - the - the theatres, until - I know the first kind of amusement that was thought of was - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Hamilton\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  wasn't it at the Free Trade Hall. They called the - the moving pictures. That was a special occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You used to go to the penny concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh they had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends or neighbours, do you think they had music or games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well only just - as I said I think I said before me mother used to have her neighbours in and - have a musical evening between themselves.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups in that time before 1918, did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No, I can't remember doing so. No, I don't - I don't think we felt we were any different - any special - you know, special group or anything. No. The only difference we saw was - in the church - most of the trustees at church lived in Whalley Range, an
d we used to feel that they were rather uppish kind, didn't we. Didn't they - Whalley Range crowd and we were ordinary crowd. 'Cos they used to come in their tall hat and frock coat you know every Sunday to church. But - otherwise - we - we didn't feel an
y different did we. Specially amongst all the Moss Side people, we all felt we - well as good as the next anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Which class would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I don't know. Don't know, like to have said we were middle class but I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well they were all - just like us, all members of the church and that and - all - all seemed equal with each other. Nobody seemed to be swanking more than the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What sort of people do you think belonged to the other classes you've mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Whalley Range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - we - of course we thought of them as - as being the upper class because they had such - terrifically big house you know, t
hey all - all lived there. Those houses now are made into flats and things. And of course they subscribed to the church and gave a lot of money for them. They - and they took charge of everything nearly didn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort different from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No, never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you ever told to touch your cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only at school we had to - for the headmaster. But not for the teachers. If the headmaster passed you always had to - touch your cap.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I can't remember because I - I never remember going out with mother - at all. With being away from home so much y
ou know and then - working after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In the district where you lived who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't know - I shouldn't think - who were considered the most important people in Moss Side? I don't know, I suppose - I should th
ink - councillors and those kind of people, but - but it wasn't - it wasn't like a village where they have a - a Manor House you know and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So it was the doctors and the professional people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, you know in the church, the church and the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who did the shopkeepers associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well I don't know - anyone who belonged to the church of course they just mixed with any - others, but - I never remember them - specially as - as special class for people you know and mixing - with other people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What about clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Clergy. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
I - I don't think the - I don't remember a man being specially - you know - they wouldn't know them as teachers or farmers or anything, just knew them as - Mr - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What sort of people would you say went to church and which went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - they all were - the same as ourselves, seemed to be - keen on the church you know and chapel. And they - and they took part in all the meetings, parties as well and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 There was no social difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. In fact we nearly always called it the same, some called it a chapel and some called it the church. Made no difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where you lived did all the people in the wor
king class have the same standard of living or would you say that there were different groups, and can you describe a family within each group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no, I should think they were all the same. They'd all be the same - on the same level.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you think that one group felt itself }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 superior}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Not where we lived, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No, no. Never noticed it specially. NO. 'Cos I never - I didn't - the only people we mixed with of course we never knew what they were - what their jobs were really. 'Cos there - there - there were different kinds belonging to the church, some were - bri
cklayers, some were joiners and - tailors. The caretaker of the church was a tailor. And so on, and one - one of them was a confectioner, but they all seemed to - they all mixed up just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 There was no distinction at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Never think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was it possible at that time to move from one class or group to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you remember anyone who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. I never even noticed any special class distinction you know. No. Even if people thought so I - I - it never occurred to me or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember anyone ever going up in the world or down in the world and how?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I know several who - who started, you know, started w
ork like I did and - and got up - well up and - one or two - well what can I - what can I say, I - there's one particularly that - became the Lord Mayor, he was - he was - he was an insurance man. He was one that - got up in the world by - really by assoc
i
ating with these that knew that they were doing, and making money and that. But - it's only a case of - like several of them that you know that they were - just working people, and then - they gradually got better and better until you saw them with a moto
r car and that and you - you knew they'd made some money. But they were still the same people as far as we were concerned you know. But no special distinction.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady, and why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't know. I don't know - do you remember - remember anybody - oh that's, yes, Mrs Holmes. Oh yes, that was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember why she was called a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh a good family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well yes, I would - well all - each member of the family wouldn't it would be one. I was very fond of one of them that got killed in the war. Vernon. He was a real gentleman. Very good - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I don't remember that. Don't remember incident.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother ever say I'll call a policeman if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't remember it but I suppose - I suppose she will have said it once or twice but - I don't think it had any affect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How do you think he treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
I think they were more or less looked upon as - as more - more - strict than they are now anyway. I think children were more afraid of them than they are now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. A rented house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you see anything of your landlord? And what did you feel about him as a land-lord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, in - in Brooks Bar - he lived at the end of the road. He was a dentist. So we saw him fairly often, he used to do his own re
pairs. But the others - when we after we were married we didn't see the landlord very often then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you feel about him as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well he was a - when we got - when we were married it was a firm, we never - we didn't - we never saw hi
m at all, we just - just called with the rent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet and what did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, I know mother had to struggle to make ends meet. Because - I - I only had a Sund
ay suit once a week. And it - and Saturday night it came back from the pawnshop and Monday it went back again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you feel about it, what difference did it make you're your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only - we don't remember - then of
 course - I don't remember - I was away then you know in that school. So - it certainly made a - made that difference, my mother had to leave Urmston and - yes. 'Cos I know she'd be happy at Urmston, it was a nice home and a nice garden with a lot of thin
gs in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 This was because your father took ill wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, she had to leave that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have to get help from anyone, the Guardians or the parish or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, we never got - no, I never remember the Guardians then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Your uncle helped your mother when she was left a widow didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, I - I think he did, I think he made an allowance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you remember any poverty in Manchester at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - no, not - not poverty, I don't remember any. Oh Ancoats, yes, but we never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What age were you when you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What age? Twenty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How long had you known your wife then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well as I - as I said before, she belonged - to the - Gladys' friend and the Dolly's friend and then passed on to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you save up money before getting married or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents help you in setting up a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, we'd no money saved when we got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Mrs Gray is answering the questions about marriage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, we had the home, 
his mother's you see, when his mother died. We went into - that's why we got married. Because - really sooner than we should have done because the girls, they were going out to work and - they got fed up so we got married and they stayed with us you see, 
in their home. That's how it happened.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You say you didn't save up before getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How long were you engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We weren't engaged. We weren't engaged. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And you didn't save up money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You took your parents home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We just drifted into it. He al - he always said he never proposed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Tell me about the wedding, did you have presents and a lot of guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Yes. He was a Sunday school teacher. And I was - I was at Sunday school, and they bou
ght us a very nice wedding present. Of course the war was on you see, the war had just started 1914. So we hesitated really whether to get married or not, whether to risk it but we did. My people went to live at Blackpool and I was - alone, in - here, I d
idn't want to go to Blackpool. So of course we got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How long did you live in this house, what address was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, we were married in Gaythorp Street but we didn't stay there very long, we went moved to Wellington Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where were you the longest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
In Wellington Street. And we stayed - then the war started, we were only there - no well - yes, we weren't long in Wellington - Gaythorp Street. The war - the war was on, and then Mr Gray had to go in the Army you see. But - he didn
't - he was - he didn't go - it was about two years, because he was grade B, you see, and - he wore glasses and they didn't take him so soon. And then - we gave up the home, 'cos I couldn't keep it on and I went back home to my people in Blackpool.;

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 While he was at the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, I went to - I went and stayed with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Mr Gray was twenty-four when you were married, how old were you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We were both twenty - twenty-four, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me what Mr Gray did when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In what way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What was his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He was in the - he was - in the warehouse, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Then after that he went to be a rap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did your husband feel about his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - well he - he wanted something better. He always 
felt as though he wanted something better. That was why of course he - he went to night school you see, 'cos he was - in the Army first, two or three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have a job after marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I didn't go out to business, I was - I stayed at 
home, my father was - they were in - they had a shop - shops you see and I stayed at home, I didn't go out to business
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You had two children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me if either of them were born before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, Lawrence was born 1915. Yes. Yes. Yes, he was '15.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was he born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 YES. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you know what to expect in childbirth before the children were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, not really. Not - I - well I mean - oh in - I knew what was happening, but - of course I didn't go ou
t to business and I didn't - pick things up quite the same, I was really - a little bit ignorant sort of thing, to some of them you know. I knew all - main things of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any medical help when Lawrence was born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I - I had a - ve
ry bad time. I - you see, I - had rickets as a child and I nearly lost my life and then - yes, that's why I'm so small. And - I - I nearly - I was very ill then. And - I nearly lost Lawrence and I was lucky to have him because I - I'm also the rare blood 
that I didn't know about. And I had a very bad haemorrhage of course and - and of course they couldn't - they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
' give the blood in those days, had they done they would have killed me I suppose. And then you see - I didn't have any more children, I had to have an operation then before I had - before }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 
Malcolm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 was born, and we were very pleased - well I was, very pleased when I knew I was going to have another one, I never wanted an only child. Mr Gray was a bit - worried about it of course. But - then I - 
I did have another, I did have Malcolm. He was - about seven months, well, nearly eight months baby. And - then I - I had four operations after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When Lawrence was born did you have any help from anybody, did any of the relations or neighbours help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 
We had an old lady that lived next door and she was a very dear old soul And - she had a girl that she took in, her husband was on the Army and she had a little girl and she was homeless, and she took this girl in and she looked - after 
he and did for her and they were both very, very kind to me, both of them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 They helped a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have a nurse in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. She - just - yes, I had a nurse. She just came in, and - and the doctors of course, I had to have doctors. And
 - she was quite a good nurse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How long did she come to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 She came - how long did she come to see me? About - a fortnight. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you feed your first baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I didn't. No. I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me how you fed them then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 On the bottle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What kind of milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - I tried different ones and then I had to go on to - oh, it's the expensive one I've forgotten it now. I forget which it - Allenbury's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 That was the expensive one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, it was but it - nothing else would suit him. And they were - they were both born with jaundice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If you needed advice who did you ask?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I used to go to the old lady next door. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If the baby was asleep would you wake it for a feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If it cried before the normal time would you feed it - if it seemed hungry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 If I thought it was - you know, if I thought he was really hungry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How long did you allow it to go on feeding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh they used to feed them 'til they was - twelve months old, more. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Then you put it on solid food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - yes, I started - yes, oh before that, I really had started with - puddings and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you wean the baby suddenly or gradually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I never fed him - I didn't - oh off the milk - no, I put him on puddings and - you know, things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did he mind going to solid food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, he didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 seem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  to be any trouble. Oh no, after about - after I got the right food he was a bonny baby, he was a lovely baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you think it did a baby any harm to let it cry or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well I didn't used to spoil him, if I thought he was - if I thought he was comfortable I wouldn't spoil him, I - I used to let him cry a while, but not for any length of time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever punish it when it was naughty and for what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, it was - they were checked. You know. And - my husband was always very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 fair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  with them though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did he have anything to do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 with}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  the babies when they were under a year, did he feed them or bath them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Or change his nappies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He did - well I don't know that he changed - well if I wasn't well he would do it, not changing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He'd change nappies then would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, but - otherwise - but I always used to - I always 
used - I used to have them bathed usually before he came home. And - they'd have their tea, and then he always took them to bed. He always - he - he took - of course there was ten and a half years between them but - you always took them up to bed didn't y
ou? And in the night he would get up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Mr Gray. I - I tried to sing Lawrence to sleep once. When Lawrence was a baby. I was just - nursing him, he said, sing to me daddy. So I started singing. And he looked and - he said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 that
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  not singing. So I've never sung another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you discuss the housekeeping between you in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Oh we've always - one. We've always been - we've always worked together. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You always discussed it with your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And we've always - we've not - I don't think either of us has ever - deceived one another, we've always told one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He gave you his packet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many rooms were there in the house in Wellington Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well there was - three bedrooms - there w
as two bedrooms and - the - they'd really had three bedrooms but the - one had been made into a bathroom, you see. So there was like three rooms upstairs. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So you had a room for bathing in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any paid help in your house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have relatives or lodgers living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Not in Wellington Street. But - after the war my father bought a house. You couldn't get a house so he bought a big one in Shrewsbury Street. Five roomed - five bedrooms. And then I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me if you did your own washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you make the family's clothes or mend them or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, I used to make the clothes, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  clothes when they were young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your husband mend the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Not - he has tried to do it, he did occasionally but not often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember where your clothes were bought? And what occasion they were bought for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I don't really, I used to just get them, go down Stretford Road
 and if I saw anything I liked I'd get it. And then mother used to buy me - clothes sometimes for the - for Lawrence when he was little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me what jobs your husband did in the home and how he helped you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh he did all the decorating and - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did he help with housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well, no, I didn't leave him much housework to do, I used to think he'd done enough when he came home, and then he used to go to night school you know, I didn't used to leave that for him to do. But 
he used to do the decorating and - like that, make things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did he ever look after the children when you were out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, he does - always look after them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did the boys have regular tasks to do at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, he - he used to make them clean their shoes you know and do little things, Lawrence used to do shopping and - that sort of thing.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember what time you made them go to bed when they were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, yes, we always - we always liked our evenings. Yes. We never let - we never allowed them up late.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever manage to get out together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, we didn't often go out. Well we didn't - very rarely. We never had the money. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 The two boys slept in one bedroom and you slept in the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You had your bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me where you ate your meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - we had a very big kitchen - oh in Wellington Street? Oh we had it in the - in the living room. You see we had a - we had the - the sitting room an
d then we had the living - the living room dining room and then a big kitchen, but we always had meals in the - in the - in the dining room you know, the living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there any special occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well no really, because that was the best room, you used to keep - I mean, it was the biggest room really for eating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Where did you cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In the kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What kind of equipment did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I had a - a - a fire oven. Oh I used to cook - I had 
the fire - the old fashioned fire range in the kitchen ovens. I used too cook in there, I did all my cooking in there. Used to make all my own bread and cakes and everything. Still do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When? Well about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who was present, did you all have it together?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, the children used to be - Lawrence was up a little later than - we used to get up about half past six. Have breakfast about seven.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember what you had for meals, what about breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't remember now, I think we just - just had what we fancied you know. Sometimes
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What about dinners, did you have meat, how many times a week would you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, well, we had - we used to have a good dinner. Of course you could get the meat cheap in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What about teas then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Tea? Well I used to bake and I used to make cakes and - and jellies and custard and that sort of thing for the children and - you know. Well I - I cooked - well you could - you could buy a 
ham you know for two shillings. A - a - a full ham for two shillings. And if we were having visitors I used to - I used to buy those, cook them you know. Do that, it was - ham was the cheapest. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you bake your own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. I still do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Bottle fruit. Did all that. Bottled fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you make wine or beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, I've made wine, I've not made beer, we don't drink beer. We're teetotal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever make your own medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Not medicine really. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could you grow vegetables when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Did we? Yes, we - we - we have grown them, we - he - with an allotment he'd - you know, he had - but my brother had an - an allotment and - then we had a - he used to do a few - and we've done it since we've been here, we've grown vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have livestock at all, hens or goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever get tinned or dried vegetables or fruit when you were bringing your family up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't think there was a 
lot of tins, we used to get the dried, the prunes and that but - there wasn't really - you - well, not when they were very - perhaps as we got a bit older there'd be - pineapple, things like that. But I used to do mostly fresh fruit. But a tin of pineappl
e chunks in those days for about fourpence you know. But mind you your wages wasn't much more than a pound a week. When we were married, was it? We managed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many times a week would you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh we used to get the meat and - and - of course you could get it for - sixpence a pound you know, the stewing meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Now often would you be able to eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - twice - twice or three meats. Yes, we - we used to have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever have tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No, we never tinned meat, it was - it was always fresh meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever have to go short so that the children or your husband could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - yes, we did, when - once when Ralph was out of - when he was out of work we had - we did go short then because th
ere was no dole, and it was when he came out of the cotton. And we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So you did have him out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you manage in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - I don't know, we managed. I remember the - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 There was no dole or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No dole. No, no dole. Of course father - we did - you see we were in father's house and he - we just had a little bit of money - that we had saved, not much. But we were - we were very careful, we never spent, it was always put down, everythin
g was put down what we spent. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Our coal - coal and light we used to put half a crown a week away for that, and by the time we got a ton of coal in, the money was there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You see? And sometimes it was - some over. Well of course - that would come in for buying shoes and different things. Yes. Oh yes, a lot of people were very - poor in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were the children allowed to talk or not at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, well - yes, because - my husband thought we - we should talk at mealtimes because that's one 
place where you're all together and you should - and you get to know one another. And he always thought you should do that. Yes. But - they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could the children choose what they wanted to eat or did they have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We
ll they had - yes, we used to - we didn't allow them to finicky, we couldn't. They had to have it, and they - they weren't bad, they - there wasn't - really things that they didn't - you know, they - they weren't funny over their food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Would they leave anything on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Not unless they weren't well. No, they would always eat it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And they could ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. If we had it, yes, if -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you tell them to hold their knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes. He was always particular about the table. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they have their own places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. They were never allowed to - they always had to ask - to leave. And he wouldn't allow - if we - if he wanted to go off in a h
urry and - we hadn't finished, he - he'd make them sit a little while. Not too long but just a little while, he wouldn't let them dash off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, I used to serve it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who did you serve first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I don't know - I don't know. I think - I think the children got it first, I think - I think I used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You didn't favour your husband?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I - I don't think so, he wouldn't let me. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What about when the children were too young to feed themselves, how did they feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, we had a high chair. Yes. We had a high chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How old would they be when they came to the table with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh about - well we used - when - as soon as they could sit in the high chair I should think about six months old we
 used to put them - near the table you see, they had their own chair and - they weren't at the table, but yet there was one - they was with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When the children were young did you feel that there was a right and a wrong way to bring them up, and did 
you and your husband have the same ideas about bringing up children or did you have different ideas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No, not at - we didn't - we didn't differ a lot, we - I think we pretty well both had the same ideas because we used to talk things over. You know, and the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You're very happily married aren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, we've been very happily married, yes. Well, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 finest}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  husband in the world
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was there anyone you used to talk to if you were worried about your children? Was your mother alive when your children were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, but she was at Blackpool you see. I used to talk to my husband if I was worried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And your mother-in-law wasn't alive when the children were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. She wasn't, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me some of the things you and your husband felt you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 out}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 t to do for your children, like affection or safety or food or discipline, and did you want them to share their worries with you, this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, not - not when they were young because we thought they'd get wo
rries soon enough of their own and they didn't - we didn't think they should, and we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 used to talk in front of them if we'd any worries. That was a very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you think was important for them to learn as they came up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 To - in what way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What things did you feel you ought to do for your children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - their dad used to help them with their homework and - he was very interested in their schoolwork. And - you know, nearly always tried to do the - we tried - we always tried to 
let them have the best. Of course - with Lawrence - he should have gone - he should have gone really but - just at the time you see, his - his dad was out for the work - out of work and he couldn't - we couldn't really do what we wanted to do, we did our 
best. And then the same thing happened with Malcolm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was affection very important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I think affection for the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You think it's very important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I do, because - even now we've got our boys and they both - they're both very affectionate, they're both very good. And they come. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 They're both very, very good.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you let them join in if grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - it just depend on the subject. You see, if - if - interesting for them, yes, we would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you bring them up to consider was important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well, to be truthful. And to - and to do a - a good deed - if they could. There was one thing that dad would never allow them to - if anyone - asked them to go an errand he would never allow them to take
 money for it. Yes. And I remember one time he was going - he used to - he was going shopping for me, Lawrence, the eldest one, he was going shopping and - he was going to Kershaw's and it's a shop where they sell all cheap fruit and that and he was takin
g
 his little truck, that his dad had made him, and he saw a lady with a - a - carrying a - big aspidistra, about - plant. He asked her where she was going. So - she told him, he said, well I'm going, he said, I'm going to Kershaw's, he said, would - would 
y
ou like to put it in my - in my - box. So she thanked him very much, so he says, have - when he got there he says - she says, well you - I'll take it now. He says, well have you far to go? She said, no, not very far. He says, well I'll take it for you. So
 he took it and she offered him money and - he said - no thank you, he says, I'm a Scout and that's my deed for - good deed for the day. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Say someone hit Lawrence, would you tell him to hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I don't know. They weren't really fighters wasn't our boys, either of them really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were there any children you discouraged them from playing with at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, yes, the - there was - if - if we thought they weren't a very good influence. Yes. Yes. But - I don't - I don't - we didn't really
 come up against that very much though, he used to go to the - he used to go to the school and they had their interests there and join - the - were in the Scouts and the - Malcolm when he went to the Grammar school he joined the Meccano club and the - dif
ferent clubs at the Grammar schools. Both of them did that - really we hadn't much trouble with - well Lawrence was one that didn't go out very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Suppose they did something you didn't approve of who punished them, was it you or Mr Gray?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - we both agreed to do the same thing I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How did you punish them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh sending them to bed. Yes, without toys or books or anything. We wouldn't allow them - if they went to bed they went - they were punished and they had to go to bed, not to read in bed or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you think you or Mr Gray played the most important part in bringing them up or do you think they go their ideas from both of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I think from both }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  us, don't you dear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You and your husband always talked everything over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes, well we do - we - we do now and - I would never dream of - I mean - in like spending money or anything like that, I - please myself, you know, what I do but I wouldn't go and buy anything without asking first - if - if - if he'd like it or
 - you know, we always like to - enjoy it together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And if the child was-punished you always talked it over and never went against each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no, we'd try not to do - we thought - well - sometimes if - if I - a question sometimes it was me t
hat got a little bit - you know, hot headed sort of thing and I would go off the deep end sometimes but - if I had - said anything, Mr Gray would tell me, he'd say, now I don't think you should have done that, I don't think that was the right thing to do,
 but he'd be nice about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And it was always when the children weren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
And when the children weren't there. Yes, we - we - we never did it - I don't now, I don't like to hear - people - I don't like to hear - man and wife quarrelling one 
an other in front of the children, I think it's very wrong for the child and - also for the - one another, they can't - they can't have happy married life if they're going to do that. Lawrence came and of course he'll just swear now and again and I said, 
Lawrence, I says, you know you've never heard your dad doing that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So you didn't like them swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh no, I don't - I don't like to hear them swear. And I said to - I says, you never heard your dad swear. He says, mum, he says, you don't expec
t me to be like me dad, he says, to be on the same pedestal as me dad, be says, there's not another man in all the world like me dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When your children had a birthday would it be different from any other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. We always - they always - we've always tried to make them up a little birthday party and - oh we've had fun on birthdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they have presents too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, they'd have the parties and - they've had games, we've arranged games for them. He's been just as interested as - as I've been.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you do specially on Christmas day as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well, on Christmas Day as a family we used to get - we used to put all the things in stockings and then - we'd get up and we'd get the breakfast first. And then we would open
 all our presents after breakfast. And - we still do that, we go to Lawrence's and we still do that. We still open all our parcels, we - we still have Christmas and stockings and - and Malcolm does the same with his children. But we've always done that ha
ven't we, we've always had a lovely Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any musical instruments in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, we had a piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did anyone sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. It was - a pity really but - we always encouraged them to bring their friends home as they got
 older. Yes. And - Lawrence - Malcolm - and Elsie, his wife, they belonged to - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 dramatics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
, they're very fond of dramatics, both of them. Well they used to have their rehearsals and - sometimes they couldn't have them in the church where they were you s
ee, they - perhaps they needed the room. So Lawrence used - Malcolm used to say, mum, can - can they come home on a Sunday? Well, we always encouraged them to bring their friends home. So I - I used to just make a cup of tea and a sandwich or - bit of cak
e
 for them, and they'd - they'd - I'd put it on the dinner wagon and they'd take it in, I didn't interfere, I just used to go in and speak to him and I used to leave them to it, and they - used to never the rehearsal and it was the same with Lawrence when 
they young, his cousins they - the played. And they - they were very - very friendly, they come - they used to come round, they used to go there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 We - we're not a musical family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you play games with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Used to play games with them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have books, newspapers, magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh very - oh, books, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 From the library or did you buy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Library. Well, it just depended - he - he would let the
m have a comic but it - but he - but he would choose it, he wouldn't let them have any kind of comic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When the children were little did you take them out visiting friends or relations or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, yes, we took them out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Both of them took you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, we always went together. Yes we always went together, unless it was afternoon and - he was working you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you take them out shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they ever go out with just their father at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, yes
, perhaps Sunday morning he would take them out when - you know, especially when they were from me, if I was getting the dinner you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He used to take them out in a pram?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, he often used to take him out - take them out in a pram.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you do on Bank Holidays, did you do anything special?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - you see mother lived at Blackpool, very often we would go home. We'd go to Blackpool you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, we didn't - not to go away we didn't have holid
ays, only at home, to go to Blackpool you see. We used to go to mother's at Blackpool, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days or Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, sometimes Saturday afternoon we would go shopping. wed go down Stretfo
rd Road, we lived in Shrewsbury Street, we'd walk down the main road shopping. And then in the evening of course the children were put to bed and then we would read. Or sometimes he used to do -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You never went out and left them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You never had anybody to look after them while you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No. No, we never - only once, a friend of ours, he - he - he was - he was staying with us, he'd come from Newcastle and he was staying with us, and he said - he said, there's a wonderful pictur
e on, he said, and I'm going to book for you, you must go. I said, no, I said, I can't. I said, I've got to get Malcolm to bed, I said, I must - bath him and put him to bed. He says, I'll bath - I'll bath him, you go. He said, I've booked for you, you'll 
have to go. But, he said, if you're not in for nine o'clock, he says - I shall have the door locked against you. And I think that's the only time we ever went out. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you attend a place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Both of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. He was - he was Sunday school teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, he did, yes, I couldn't go with the children, not until they got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you belong to the choir now you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I used to when I was - before I was - before I was married you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did this chapel run a temperance club and did you belong to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, we - we both went to the same, that was where we met.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 It was still the same chapel was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And you still had the same activities and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes. Everything, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your children got to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes, both of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they ever go to an adult service with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 They used to come to chapel with us, yes. Yes, they used to come chapel with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you say grace at meals or did you have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No - we had - when they were young we had - we had grace, the children used to say it. Yes, they used to do then in those days a lot you know, used to have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you say prayers at night as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, they used to say their prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Who taught them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well both of 'em, their dad and me, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you take an interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 NO.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When your husband wasn't doing his work how did you spend your time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I never had any time. I'd be either - sewing or knitting or making or cooking or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And your husband always stayed in with you, he never went out and left you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. Unless it was - unless it was something a
t the church he'd gone to and - only at the church. We never went out on our own did we? We never went out
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did either of you go to a club or institute or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He's teetotal, he doesn't - he won't - he doesn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you belong to savings clubs, boot clubs, sick clubs or funeral clubs or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh the - we had the - no, just insurances you know, for death and that sort of thing
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did either of you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Only when the children were - we were interested in them you know when they went, but not ourselves. No, oh no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You couldn't go to theatres or music halls because you couldn't get out could you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well no, and then Mr Gray was deaf you see, he's been deaf since the first world war so we've not really been interested in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any hobbies, keep any pets, collect anything or do gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh gardening. Oh yes, that's his main hobby, gardening. Oh yes. And that's what I worry about because he's got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 angina}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  you know and he's got to be very careful, he doesn't go out, he never goes out. Not now, he can't do with walking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did anyone outside the home help you look after the house or family, relatives or friends or neighbours, when you were ill or anyt
hing like that how did you manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - not 'til recently. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Before 1918 when the children were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no, no. Nobody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How about when Lawrence was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well - no, I didn't have - oh those - that - lady next door, yes, I had her, she came in and - came in and helped me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You had such a paragon of virtue in Mr Gray that you didn't need any help did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. No. We had a lot of - lot of sickness you know but still we got through. And the boys have been very good
, they're both very - very good in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they have jobs to do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well yes, and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 they\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  did it voluntary though when - when I was hospital you know, they would do - both of them would both do anything. They were both very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Not too near. There was one - in Chorlton, they weren't too far away, we used to visit them sometimes. But of course they're all gone now, we - I've no brothers, I've no one now. Only our two boys.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have a lot of friends then and did you have them in the house and did you visit them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh yes, we visit them and they - they visited us, brothers - my brothers, we always got on very well and my sister-in-law's, we always got on very well with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were they your friends or your husband's of both your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So really they were both of your friends that came to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, if - if anyone's coming be both our friends, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you have a lot of visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well - they used to come in and see us you know, a lot of friends. We always had a - and we still have people call you know, still have friends that call and see us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did they come for meals or did they just call in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Occasionally.
 Well, not a lot to be - well sometimes, we'd make them a cup of tea and that you know but - they didn't - my brothers - the family did, but - we didn't have - they used to come sometime from the chapel, you know, friends from the chapel, you - of course 
when you go to chapels you've always a lot of friends and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you go out visiting them too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. Yes, we used to go - I used to go - I used to play tennis when I was younger, with - the tennis club you know, sort of thing. And people - from the chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 People often tell us that in those days when they had friend in they made their own amusement, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you play music or games?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh used to do all sorts of things, yes. Yes. We always made our own amusements, it's amazing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What kind of things did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I don't know. As - I don't really know. We always seemed to pass the time you know and - I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well, if the children - we'd play with the children,
 we'd play games with them you know. We - we'd play games with the children then. Used to make party you know when it was birthdays, Christmastime, we'd make parties and - and arrange games. Those had all been arranged so as they wouldn't be bored. Made t
h
ings you know. I remember one year we were making - party and we had that much icing was stuck up, he was putting all the names on the cakes and we made dominoes and - for the - for you know, for the party, I don't know whether it was a birthday or Christ
mas. Made boats with paper sails and - oh I loved it, I love doing anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And so did Mr Gray did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh he helps, yes. He helps with the - you know, doing things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Part of the time - well - it was - the house before we came here, it was father's house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 But before that you were in a rented house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He left that to me, that house you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When you were first married you were in a rented house weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Yes. And then after the war the one - father's house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you ever see anything of your landlord and what did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh he was very nice. We got on all right. I've always been very fortunate, I've always had nice neighbours and got on well
 with people, it's - always had nice neighbours, I've never ever had disagreeable - neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You stayed in the same district more or less when you were married didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. And then - 'til we came here. Then we moved from - Brooks Bar to here you see. That was - we bought this house then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 That was well after 1918 wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 That was well after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Tell me about your married life, your husband can't hear so you can tell me about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh, we've no secrets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 Tell me about the children and your marriage in general, it was obviously very, very happy wasn't it?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh yes, we've been very happy. We've had our ups and downs of course. We've been without - you know, we know what it is not to have money coming in and then he
 - he got a - he got a - a job. He was helping a gentlemen to sell tea. And he went all the way to Sale and he lost his mac. I think he made about tuppence. Lost his mac. Yes, when he was out of a - didn't you? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What are the happiest things you remember about your marriage looking back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
You know, one of my happiest days was when he came back from the war. When I got the telegram - to say that he was coming back. That was the - one of my very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 happiest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  days. I knew he was come - he was coming home, yes. Because he'd be expecting coming home from - for a long time, he was in France and been expecting coming home for a long time. And he - he didn't. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 And - then he wrote me a letter saying that he was going farther into France and I was very, very downhearted, I thought, oh he's not coming home. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And then - I was cleaning the front at Blackpool, and I saw a boy coming and I thought, now I do hope this boys not coming when I've done the front, I do hope he's not going walking up these steps, because th
ey were very wide steps you see, mother had a boarding house. Anyway, I'd just gone to change the water for the steps and the bell rang, and I thought, oh goodness, he's - up me steps. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 
Feeling very cross about it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Anyway when I got there it was the telegra
m boy with a telegram Needless to say I never finished the steps. I didn't - I - I used to put Lawrence to bed when we were at home you see when I went home and he was a baby and Ralph was in the Army, I used to - put him to bed about half past five to si
x
, I've always had him in bed early, and - of course I was - I bathed him, got him in bed, it was Saturday. Oh he - on the telegram he said that - by the time you read this I shall be in Manchester. 'Cos he was just calling - I think he was calling at the 
t
ailors or something and he was saying what time he'd be back. So, I thought, well - Lawrence hasn't seen his daddy for - for a long time now. Oh I should think it was twelve months. So of course I - I was keeping him up, well I knew he'd want to see him y
o
u see. Oh, father cross with me, he - said, put him to bed, he said, he's falling asleep, you - you'll see - we've all the rest of the days. I said, he's not - I', not putting him to bed. I said, I'm taking him to meet his daddy. So I did, I took him. Too
k him to the station to meet him. It was about - half past eight, he was very very tired.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What do you think is the secret of the happiness of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I think - the secret is - is - is trusting one another and - and - not - not keepin
g things from one another. I think - however unpleasant it is I think it's better to tell one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You think this is the reason you've been so happy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh I do. Yes. I do. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Apart from the fact that you think a great deal of each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh yes, we always have done, yes. It'll be - the only thing now we're both eighty. Well - I'm not eight - I'm not eighty 'til July. I'm in my eightieth year, a few weeks now. He's turned eighty. I feel - however great the loss I - I'd rather him go
 before me, I don't want to leave him. I - I feel nobody can hurt him then and being so deaf - because I know it wouldn't be very long after. Well I wouldn't want it to be. But - still I shall have me memories. But I - I - I - I feel that way, that I - I'
d rather he go first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Then you've always looked after him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. And he's looked after me too, but I - I feel that I - I can do better than he can do if I was left. You know, to - I wouldn't like - because, he's so very sensitive you know, he's ve
ry touchy and very sensitive. Very soon in tears you know. With little children or anything, if you read anything in the paper he chokes he can't - he can't read, he can't tell you. And he is like that. He'd be so lonely. No, I don't - I - I'd like - howe
ver - however - it would be a loss to me but - I'd rather it be that way. I don't want to - to leave him you know. Yes, we are - we've been very happy. We are, yes, still very happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You don't know why she thinks you're so wonderful?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Mr Gray. No idea.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What's made your marriage so happy then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I suppose she doesn't know me specially yet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What do you think makes a happy marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well we - we - we agree on everything don't we. We have little differences, but no quarrels. You know, we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 differ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  with different things but - don't squabble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Mrs. Gray. We don't always agree you know, it - well it wouldn't be right would it. Couldn't do that. But we don't - we don't fall out, we never - we never got to - we - wouldn't go 
to sleep without kissing one another good night you know. Wouldn't do that. Even - even if we felt a bit niggly or a bit hurt we wouldn't do that. No.</subject2>
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You've obviously got the secret of happy marriage haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Mr. Gray. Well - we
ll our marriage - I'm only small myself. And she was a bit smaller than me and that's the type I like. See. And - I didn't want a wife as I had to look up to. And I look down like that and you know - that - I think that was the first - I - think that caus
ed it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So it's just as well you had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 rickets}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  isn't it? Rickets is unusual isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Mrs. Gray. Yes. Now. It is now, it wasn't in those days. No. You see, they - they didn't -</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Why did you have rickets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well it must have b
een short of something. It - it must have the milk and eggs and all that sort of thing you know, it must have been - it must have - I wasn't a very strong person, my mother wasn't very strong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 But your father had a good job didn't he in the insurance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh father was all right but - yes, he - oh yes, he was all right, he - but father was a man that - he was fond of himself. He thought a lot of mother. But he was fond of himself too, you know, he - he - he saw that he was right. And mother was a bit
 I think she really spoiled him you know - if they - well they shouldn't have been short of milk in those days because there was plenty of milk and it was cheap, but he could always have his pint of milk - and when we were little - that had to be saved fo
r father, whether there was enough for any-one else or not although - mother would have let us have it you know but he always liked his pint of milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You say you were afraid of your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I mean - well I was, to a certain extent - mind you he was a good father. He was a very good father. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16472563\charrsid8081393 But he was very, very stern and - if - if - well, it's like this now, if I was going to Sunday school I was never allowed to - he was a - he was superintendent of the Sunday school, and I was never allowed to b
e late, and if I - I remember on one occasion I'd called for one of my little friends and I wasn't really late, not really, but he stood on the platform and he started the - service and he made he go onto that platform and sit on the platform and that was
 a terrible thing for me to do.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Because you were late?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Because - yes. He said, where had I been, I was sent out early enough and it was wrong in front of the school you see. Wasn't right, that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So he was a stern father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And - well my 
mother was very cross about that when we got home. She said he'd no right to have done it. He said, well she must learn to do as she's told. You know and I always remember it. And I - oh I never forget going and sitting up there and everybody looking at m
e, it was terrible. Because - I wasn't very strong as a child and I was very nervy you know I was very frightened, he did a lot of harm to me that did. It was wrong. Shouldn't do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 There's a big change in discipline isn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Oh yes. 
Mother was very - temperate. My mother was - she was beautiful. She was lovely. Father was very hasty. Good man, he was - you know, he - he was good in his way but he was very short tempered. Very bad tempered. He'd get over in he wouldn't sulk. In - if h
e'd upset you, he'd - you know, he'd say, well I said nothing, I've done nothing, you know. He doesn't think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you sit down and think about it and compare your life and decide that your children would be different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, I - I - I thought t
hen that I should never - well - I think that incident did it with me more than anything. That - making me go on the platform, I thought I never would do that with my children, if ever I had any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So you talked it over what you would do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh we do
, yes, and - and even now, for birthdays and whatever it is we - we always talk it over, we - what we should do or - or if we feel that we want to give them anything - well specially Malcolm more so than Lawrence, Lawrence is in the position he doesn't ne
e
d it really, he's all right, he's - but we do give it to him, but I mean like when Malcolm has done these jobs and that time he's bought things you see we felt well - I - I've said, well don't we think - don't you think you ought to give him something mor
e? He'll say, yes, if you want him, what do you want to give him, it's quite all right. Now he's - we've been having a - bedroom - we've been doing the bedroom upstairs, it - the - my help has }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 done}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 eiling for us and - Malc
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 ol}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 m's come in and done some of
 the papering, bit of the painting, and he's also taken the fireplace out, which was quite a big job. And he's plastered it all up and he's made a beautiful job of it. So I said to his dad, he - he was paying him like for the material for the plastering a
n
d the different stuff so I said, well - we're playing him for doing the kindness. He said, and I think he should do that little kindness for us. But anyway in the end he decided he would. I said, well, I said, it was Easter love, he says, and you know whe
n all's said and done, I said, he is - he has been working his holiday. He says, yes, he has. Well of course nothing more was said.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember Christmas at your home, did you have Christmas presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, always had a nice Christmas, yes
. My - my, yes, we did, we always had a good Christmas. We always had a lot of visitors, we had a lot of visitors from the chapel. Of course my mother and father were very big workers. My mother was a very big worker in the chapel. And we used to - we use
d
 to have many times, if ministers used to come to preach - when they'd come from a way they'd stay - stay with us, of course they were in business you see. They were in the boot and shoe trade. Father had three or four shops. Yes, he had three or four sho
ps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So he only went into insurance later on in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes, it was when - he bought an insurance book. He gave - well he was going to Blackpool, he was buying this house at Blackpool. Anyway he bought an insurance book and I - I don't know why he d
id that, he had to buy it. And then they decided no, he - they decided they'd have this house at Blackpool, he give - he gave it - the shop wasn't doing too well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 This was before the first world war too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Yes. The shops wasn't doing too w
ell so he decided that he'd - they decided to take a boarding house at Blackpool. So they bought this in Albert Road. Big place. And - mother and my sister went over and father stayed in Manchester. They took a small house, in Bollington Street then. And 
-
 they - just kept it temporary you see and - father used to go over in the summer at the weekends but I stayed and looked after the house in Bollington Street with my two brothers, they weren't married. And then - I think that lasted for - nearly two year
s. And then of course he sold this book. He was a long time before he could sell his book for some reason or other, I don't know why. But it was a long time. So - but in the end he did sell it and of course when they went over to Blackpool but - and I -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 This was the book of poems you wrote to your wife, read me the one about your Golden Wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Mrs Gray. The journey has been rocky, but we've reached the harbour now. With such golden treasures garnered on the way as two loving sons who God rest wi
th our coming days and now with the grace of sweet contentment. Merrily play that the golden bands of love that we for fifty years have know will keep us still together, 'til life's setting sun goes down.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 This is the one you wrote when you were in the Army away from your wife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Each hour drags slowly as with lonely heart my daily tasks I cheerfully strive to do. And wonder in my - in my leisure hours apart thinking of home and you. And when the daylight fades and shadows creep up from t
he valley duty is carried through sweet it's indeed to lower my soul in sleep dreaming of love and you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 This is called We Are Seventy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 That's on our seventieth birthday. Age - age has not dimmed the love of youthful days, we journey still benea
th it's radiant glow. The loved companions if life's sunny ways, true helpmates when through darker paths we go. I pay that now we'll never knew the plight when you or I will have to walk alone. But when life's twilight warns of coming night, still hand i
n hand we'll see the sun go down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 The number of children at Cheadle Hulme school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Number of - of children? Oh I - I couldn't exactly remember, should think there'd be about - be about two hundred I should think. About one - say about a hundred of each, boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you want to go or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh yes, I was - I - I was willing to go. But of course I didn't want to leave home. Because I didn't know what - what I was - what I was going in for. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you homesick or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. For the first fortnight after we got back after holidays. I used to - once we got into bed I used to start crying, but you know, I had a quiet cry on me own and didn't - not let anybody else know. After we'd - you know, I wanted to be back home ag
ain. But - after a fortnight I was as happy as anybody and - and 'cos I - I really liked being there, and I liked all the friends I made there - So, the homesickness didn't last long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you miss most?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I can't think really. I don't think o
f - I don't remember that we did very - very much at home, only that we - we'd been - knocked about with each other you know, my sisters and myself - and mother. But - by that time I'd got no hobbies or anything, I was only nine years old and - and nothin
g like 'til we got to the school and then started taking interest in things. But - no - it was just matter that I didn't want to leave home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How much time did you have to yourself to do as you liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - do you mean at school? Oh yes, we had - w
ell - we had - first - first of all we had what they called preparation in the morning, that was homework supposed to be. We went before breakfast to the school house. There were the two sections you see, there was the - residential part, and the schoolho
u
se was in the grounds but a bit farther off. Well we went there - before breakfast and for about threequarters of an hour doing the - homework that had been set the night before. Then we went back to - to the school for breakfast. Then we had about - half
 
an hour playing. And that was generally - most in the winter the playground wasn't available then because everybody was kicking a ball about as I mentioned. So those who weren't kicking the ball were perhaps had - sat reading or - in my case and my friend
,
 we were - on the gym - in the gymnasium, swinging about and doing that - all kinds of - fancy antics there. Well then - about nine - nine o'clock they paraded and marched across to the school again. And then they had the lessons and marched back and - an
d - about twelve o'clock and we were free 'til dinner until the dinner bell rang. But you all had to get washed, wash your hands and face. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 
And then - parade again and - and all on parade in the playroom before marching - we all had to show our hands, you know, whether they were clean or not, and those that were dirty were sent back to - to the wash -room to wash them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And if that happened, they came - came into dinner late. Well then they had to stand up all the time while having their dinner. For being late in the dining hall.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How much time did you have to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well after that - after dinner we had about half an hour again for playing. Then we had to - parade and back to school 'til four o'clock. Well then we were free 'til teatime. And then
 - we used to just play about, or whatever they wanted to do. And then - of course we had a playroom, a big playroom and a play - in the playground. Well then - by - tea would be about five o'clock. Then we'd to parade again for tea. Then what I said - us
e
d to do - last time about - we had just a mug of tea and some bread and butter. Yes. And - and - sometimes - the - they gave us a - a bun if they'd had a - if they'd had a cookery lesson. And - or on Good Friday we had a hot cross bun - for breakfast. Alo
ng with the other things, yes. And if - if they'd - the bread was gone too soon, 'cos they used two platefuls of bread for the table, well - if there wasn't sufficient -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many on a table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 There'd be - I forget just how many but I should think 
there'd be about six on each side of the table, and a monitor sat at the end. And he was in charge of that table. Well then they - they cut - of course they pass the plate to each one, then - if they were more hungry and all the bread went the end boy had
 to stand up - to indicate that we wanted some more bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Like Oliver Twist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. Well then the headmaster - there of course the teacher was sat on a platform a bit higher than us so that he could look down on us all. Well he - he'd look all ove
r the room and he could see all the tables, and he'd notice that - that one table perhaps had got a few pieces of bread left on a plate, then he'd tell the boy to go to table number so and so, then collect that plate and bring it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 And so of course they all - the same amount of bread seemed to do for the whole lot, some went short and went and got it from the other table. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh - and well we enjoyed our meals. And breakfast time they called out all the letters that they got, you know, the - they all had post of course from - parents or whoever they were and he distributed the letters.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your parents write you letters, did your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Mother did, yes. Yes. Oh she - she wrote and she used to send postage stamps, for us to put in the bank you see rea
dy for - then if we wanted anything at school - if it was a game of any kind or - ball or anything like that, you just go to headmaster and tell him what it was and he'd buy it and - take the money out of the - account. And - they did that with }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 fretwork}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  and that kind of stuff, you know, with the - with the hobbies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What did you do in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Oh in the evening we always - we always had - more or less run about games. Rally-o, I don't know whether you knew what that game was. Rally-o. And - ch
ibby. Chibby, where one - they chose the boss, as the group, and he'd have a strap in his hand. And that's all the - that's all the rules there were, that you'd to run about and if the boss saw you anywhere he'd come along and strap you on the behind. We 
h
ad to keep - just keep out of his sight. That was the only rule in the game. Seems daft when you come to think of it but - and they - and everybody liked doing it. And - they had - what they called cab at arms, the two - you know, two boys together like h
orses, and then they were holding their hand bending down and a boy on his back and - and they used to have - battles like try and knock each other off. All those kind of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What time did you go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - we were in bed by nine o' - I think it was nine o'clock, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What time did you get up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
That would be about half past six. Yes. We'd get up at half past six and - go to the washroom, a good wash ourselves, then we'd to fold our - our - night - we had - we had nightgowns then, w
hite nightgown. Not pyjamas. We had to fold that up and put it on the bed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How many to a bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well they - they had various size }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 dormitories}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 . The bigger ones, they had - I think about - two dozen - boys in. And - there - then at the top end was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 cubicle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
, a partition, for a - a teacher slept in there. Yes, oh his own, that was his own - cubicle, bed and everything, so of course he was listening to everything that went on And there was no - we had to be silent after we'd got into bed. And 
- they had a special rule - that we all - when we got undressed we'd to put our clothes and we had a wooden box at the bottom of the bed. You kept your - your clean clothes inside it and your - your best - your clothes you'd just taken off, must fold them
 
up and put them on that - that - on the box in the - in the right position, according to which - what order you're going to put them on again. Yes. Yes. And that was all right to keep you - you know - oh I can't think of the word now. - Methodical you kno
w what I mean, methodical, I've got it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How often were you allowed out for walks or church or to visit home or friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh - we were never allowed to go out - of the grounds on our own. Only - to the - to the playing field. The - the school was 
- of course it was in - more like in the country and farther - I remember where it was out of the gates - and just along the lane under the railway bridge, then that - the playing field was there. Well - we - we never were allowed on that even until we go
t
 permission. It depended on the weather. And then we'd be told that we had permission to go to the playing field, you see. Well then we were allowed to walk there and back to the playing field, but we mustn't be seen anywhere else. We're not allowed to st
ray from the haven, but of course - my friend and I, as I told - told you before, we went birds nesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 What happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And - oh no, never got caught, but I wasn't - I wasn't too keen, but there was a - my boy, he was a farmer's son, and he liked
 to collect the eggs. But anyway - I learnt a lot from him because - see the nest and tell me just what kind of a bird had laid them. So I was really learning a bit of natural history, which wasn't in the curriculum at school. And of course we were very f
o
olish because - we had pork pie caps - sit on the back of our head - with - with a school badge on it and - we were so silly, we thought if we turned the caps round the badge would be at the back and the local villagers wouldn't recognise where we'd come 
from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you allowed to wear your own clothes rather than uniform at any time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No. No. We - not our own clothes at all. The only change we were allowed was to wear a little bow to our collars, we used to have a - a - a stiff collar. Eton collar
 as they called it and - we could wear a little bow that was fastened on with elastic, well we could please ourselves what colour those were. But we couldn't wear anything else - only the school clothes. And one - rule they had, we always had to take our 
jacket off - to play about. That's why - once or twice I've been - growled at a bit for being in the house with - in my shirtsleeves and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 waistcoat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  you see with no coat. Been told - I've been told it's not proper. But yet I've been brought up to do that. As 
soon as we came out - down from the - mealtime - there's one long corridor with hooks on and all our number on. And we had to take our jacket off and hang it on that peg with that number, - to run about. And then of course at teatime, mealtime we put our 
jacket on again and - so I suppose it was to save the wear and tear of the clothes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were you allowed other personal possessions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes, we were - we were allowed - we - in the playroom we each had a locker of our own with our number on it,
 and we could keep our possessions there in that - of course nobody had anything very big, it was all - just a small one. But generally - generally games and snap and ludo and all those. And then some of them had running shoes for - for Saturday when they
 could go on the playing field. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 And - there - there was one - well there were two brothers - that had musical instruments. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
And - and then they were the only - the only two of them that I remember who had anything - rather big. But they were like clever - very clever musicians. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 
One of them special, I - his name was Vipond, I remember that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And he - he played the - he brought a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 melodeon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  once, and he could play any instrument there were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Was he allowed to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 He was allowed to play during our playtime o
f course. But - not - not officially, there's no - no official playing. There were some boys who were learning the piano and of course he - he - they asked him would he like to learn the piano but he wouldn't take that on. But he was allowed to - to play 
with it anything - while the playtime was on you see. Now what else can I tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did your mother visit you and how often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no, never - she never visited the school. Well they weren't allowed. No. They - we weren't allowed visitors at all. Ex
cept on a special occasion, like I was telling you about the other day. Like when we went to the Atheneum, and to Longsigh But otherwise nobody ever visited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you think it changed how you felt to your mother or not, did you feel more or less close to them, or much the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no - oh - close to them, I mean to say - to mother you mean? Oh yes. I was very pleased to - see her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you think it changed how you felt to mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No, I don't think so. No, I don't think so, I thought just a
s much of her when - when we got home. That's why I used to cry when we got back. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did you meet children of a sort you'd not met before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - I didn't notice they were - they were all - all more or less the same - as ourselves and - and
 of course we were just at the age when we didn't realize there were such things as - as wealthy people and poor people you know, we were - we were just - we were in a community where every - everyone on the same level and - we assumed that everybody had 
mothers and fathers at home just the same. But - we just - they just chose their own friends and - never thought where they came from or - what type of home they'd come from. Which was all to the good I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 When you came home did you spend your time differently from how you had before? Were they the same friends as before or new ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No, I just - seemed to settle into - routine with everything else. Only that - of course we did - went round to know the neighbours and they all came asking ques
tions One's asking how we went on. And - I know there was one particular family that - always thought we'd gone to college. Yes, they were asking how had you gone on at college. And, oh I - I wish I could have gone to college, you know. So I suppose reall
y
 that helped to - to make us feel a little important. Being - but stop - but they'd stop it, though we didn't realize it but mother did, was the wearing the school uniform - on holidays. Because it was so noticeable. It was a special - suit, they had the 
short trousers and long stockings with no fancy tops they - they had - come over the knee and with garters. Yes. And then the trouser came down to there. And the jacket - there was - had no collar on, we used to wear the collar }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 outside}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  the jacket, like the 
Eton school do, but the jacket had one button at the top and hanging open down - down that - like that you see. Like - that's what they and - being - me and boy Ryland, John Rylands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Were they supplied free?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Free? Oh - oh we were provided with t
hem - because we - we never had to provide them and - if you grew out of them they just change them for somebody else. And overcoats, they had - I think they were called Ulster. Long - long coat with a - a long cape on. But we didn't - we didn't possess t
h
ose. We were being - we tried - we paraded and - each one given a coat to try on and they came and - to see which fitted, whether - and - and they found one to fit you, and then that was put into a little cubby hole, up on - on one of the ladings, with yo
u
r number on, and that - it was put in there and you were never allowed to touch it after that. Unless - on special occasions, for instance if we went in church on the Sunday, 'cos we used to parade and march to church. And if it was raining this - you wor
e
 - wear overcoats. Well then we were marched round onto the upstairs along the landing and then we passed the cubic - the pigeon hole we just pulled the overcoat out and put it on. Then after church we'd to put it back again. But we never saw that in betw
een - times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 It wasn't a Dickens type home at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh no. No, it wasn't Dickens type.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 There was no cruelty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 No. Oh no. Nothing of that kind. No, they all got on very well and - the teachers were very - the teachers were very friendly a
s well. I don't know if we'd - there was no cruelty of any kind. No, never felt it - because all the others were the same. Except the special boarders. So they never ever seemed to - didn't talk about being orphans or to feel that they were. Because I sup
p
ose - having started so young and we more or less got into the idea that - it was a normal state of affairs. You see to be orphans. We thought there were plenty of others like it you see. And - learnt afterwards that it was more or less a unique instituti
o
n. Yes. 'Cos - I mean - I never got to know where these clerks were, whether it was bosses or - but it seemed - seemed - name of it sounds as though they were not - not the bosses of firm but the employers of firms who'd got together and found that - but 
t
here's no doubt the - it was a very - very good and - well a very happy institution. I'll never regret it that I went there. And nearly everybody that - we did hear about that left all did very well in life afterwards. Yes, one or two became doctors and -
 that - things like that. They all seemed to do very well. Except me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Can you tell me what difference being an orphan meant in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - I don't know, I - even in that time I hardly realized that it was - a great big - big difference.
 It seemed to me - it seemed to me more the - the normal state of affairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Did it mean hardship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
No. I didn't realize any hardship. But of course I might have done had I stayed at home. But - you see, we were kept - mother had - mother hadn't to
 provide for us and so we didn't know of any shortages, anything like that. We - we got as much food as we needed really and got everything else. Was allowed to play as we liked. And I - we certainly got a - I wouldn't say a good education but we got a - 
a suitable one. A little bit of everything. You know, mathematics, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 Euclid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
, trigonometry, geometry and drawing. And history. Geography, Shakespeare. And carpentry, we - we had - went once a week into the carpentry shop to - to learn and - and we even had a s
ession in the - in the boiler house, with the - they called him Teddy, I don't know what he was called, his job, but we had a session there with all shoveling cinders into the boiler and things like that. So they trained us for any kind of a job we - migh
t
 have had to do. And one of the punishments if we did anything wrong - we had to - to march round the playground. They had a big playground and they had a verandah on each side and - and - and anybody who'd been reported - if the teacher thought it was mo
r
e serious than normal it'd be reported to the headmaster, well he'd be told to parade on the - at playtime, after tea and - and they'd got march round the playground so many times and for so long. The teacher had - and the teacher would be in charge, and 
h
e'd to keep on backwards and forwards along there, just marching and - that was the - that was the punishment. Instead of playing they would keep marching there. But while you were doing it you'd be talking to your friends while they were kicking the ball
 about and that and - it was only a matter that you were confined and had to keep marching. And of course many a time they were singing as they marched and all that sort of thing so - it wasn't much of a punishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Looking back on life as a child what were your impressions of life in those days generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Well I - yes, I - seemed very happy life. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 
There's one thing that - occurred to me, that we - never heard such things as strikes or - wage freezes and things like that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And even wars - 'course th
ere was - during the Boer war. Of course then - then we heard about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 In school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
The Boer War was on while we were at school. Oh yes, the - they had badges of all the Generals. YES? Baden Powell and Lord Roberts and - all the others. They h
ad a little you know, button with their picture of them on. And of course that was one of the - competitions really between the - the boys wearing the - Generals badges. And if the - we kiddies would have argument, oh - well my brother say he's no good, w
e
ll that's so and so, you know, all in good - good - I mean - never took a big interest in it. And not - I don't recall - then I remember the - the Relief of Mafeking. I don't know if you've heard of that then - we were all concerned about that, that Mafek
i
ng was - besieged. And it was about twelve o'clock at night, we were all in the fast asleep and the headmaster came round and roused us all and told us, I wish to let you know that Mafeking has been relieved. And of course we all sat up in bed and - that 
w
as one of the incidents. But we was - keen on that. And of course we were very keen on the - boat race. Oxford and Cambridge. Well they - they had - they had their blue, pale blue and dark blue ribbons. And of course - the idea of that has - set the - sup
p
ose it set the - the idea for other games. Any other games that they had, any game of rivalry, that - just at that period was - Oxford and Cambridge, come on, well the Oxford would be one side and Cambridge on the other. And if they had wrestle - wrestlin
g
 matches or things like that. And there was one game that we had, well it's still a game really, round the playroom they had wooden seats, about that wide, all round. Well - they used to - whoever got there first, there'd be perhaps six boys'd - would sta
n
d on the seat - in the corner you know, leaning - and starting in - if they happened to be Oxford they'd shove into the Cambridge. Well then the Cambridge had to get on and - and knock them off, see, and then they take possession. But they seemed to enjoy
 
- they - 'cos it all helped in the physical strength and that sort of thing. In between leavers, what they call leavers. Those that were leaving when they were fifteen. The leavers and non-leavers. And of course that'd be another thing they had rivalry fo
r
. Leaver - leavers. And then the others - the non-leavers'd start - struggling, whatever the struggle happened to be about you know. And - what they looked forward to - when they were going to leave school, they were allowed - a jacket with a - with lapel
s. And - and a - a waistcoat, a real waistcoat. And - and the over one buttoned right up to the neck you see. But - the - the leavers were allowed to have the - an open neck waistcoat and a - and lapels on their coat. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So they felt special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Yes. Well those in preparation for civvy life of course. And when we left school we got a full }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 rigout}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
. Like - like that. Yes. Every - everything - but it had to be boots instead of shoes of course. Rather heavy boots we had. And for us - the - the - we had 
a parade every so often. And a cobbler came along examining all our boots. And any that wanted repairing he took them away and repaired them. But they - they always - had big - big baskets full of boots. And he'd bring them - these round and he'd - try - 
try your boots on. If your's had gone for repair you never got them back, you'd take another pair out of there. Then they'd come back repaired you see and they'd go in the basket for next time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Do you remember any poverty before 1918 as you were growing up and working in Manchester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Well I - I wouldn't call it poverty but - mother was very hard up I know. We had - we had a lot of trouble - with - I think she had - got too many clothing clubs going and that sort of thing. And - on several occasion
s the landlord - came, he says, you're owing money. And - - as I explained in every - every Saturday night, went to the pawn shop to get my suit out. And on the Monday morning it went back again. And on some occasions, well I - I was very uncomfortable in
 
that respect, sometimes she - she hadn't the money to get it out and - I'd - I'd already joined the church then you see and my - with my friend and - sometimes I had to miss going to Sunday school and I didn't like telling - him why. And other - other occ
asions when I did go with them I kept my coat on - my raincoat on in the class and he used to ask me why don't I take my raincoat off. Because I was ashamed of the clothes I'd got underneath it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 I'd be - oh about se
venteen I think. Yes. That was just when I - I think that was about - I'd be just over sixteen I think when I first joined the church. But - I - it - even with all that we - really couldn't say we were really miserable about it. I do know - when I was tel
l
ing you about the - about my uncle helping after mother died. Then we found out see the - the terrific lot of debts left that she owed for. Of course she was a very generous person and she used to entertain anybody who came. See the - she could never refu
se - and gifts for people and that sort of thing. And then of course she'd be more hard up than ever. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You loved your mother didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Yes, I did. And even - my wife got to love her as well, she - oh she said you couldn't - she nev
er found any fault with her. And I don't - it's only about one incident when - 'cos we had a cellar in that house and - mother was very fond of pigs head - for cooking. And of course down in the cellar we had a - a mangle, a really old fashioned }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 mangle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393  and
 dolly tub and all that, well anyway - she'd got a pigs head for Sunday dinner. And she put it on - on the mangle, on a - on a dish. And then - Mrs Gray - of course I'm calling her Laura, her name - when she came round mother asked her - said she wanted s
omething out of the cellar, I forget what it was, but she asked - asked her to go - will you go into the cellar and get such a thing for me? Anyway before she got - before she - did that she'd arranged this pig}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 s head in such a position and scared the life 
out of her. And she came running up about it. She remember that, she's mentioned that many a time. That was one of the pranks she played on - and I'm sure in spite of the - hard upness and everything else she was always very lively and - always - always h
a
ppy together. Yes. She died at forty-three. 'Cos at that time we didn't realize she was as ill - only a young woman. We thought she was getting on a bit. Poor age to die isn't it. And she died of angina. Yes, that - that's - like - like I've got and my ol
der sister died of it. But of course there's no such thing as they've got now to - to - help. Those pills that - tablets that I'm taking, does wonderful to help you get - to carry on. I suppose I wouldn't be here if it hadn't been for those. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 You were saying you were rich?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
We were rich. Oh we were rich - in - in our relationship of - each of us, that's what I was meaning. You know, of our family, we're all fond of each other and we - enjoyed our life together. And so I suppose we were rich in that respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 And now you have a happy marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 So you have been rich?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes, I have. Although - they didn't like it at first. Well - mind, the only one reason. That is that she's so small. She - she's only a small - you 
see - and I - 'cos - and that was through rickets when she was young, she told us that, that - that she was bow legged at first. They've gone straighter and she's all right, but - the chief thing was that - the - the people in Germany wanted me to go over
 there, you see. The name }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890129\charrsid8081393 Graffinhof}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
 - was dying, there - there was only the two men there, and I was the only surviving male, and they wanted me to perpetuate the name. And - he'd already planned - that I should go over the same as my eldest sister went, y
ou see, and - he was very annoyed that I was courting. And of course mother more or less sided with him, she said, I - I ought to have a - a - a more noticeable person, you know, a - like a tall stately - more a stately wife who could - bring me up to - b
e a respectable gentleman. Anyway -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16413182 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 But you wanted Laura?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2819311 RG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039564\charrsid8081393 
Yes. I remember - one thing that mother did to try and - break the relationship. She told Laura - she wrote and told her I was then earning about fourteen shillings. And she told - she tho
ught it might matter. She told her that - do you know that he's only earning fourteen shillings a week? He can't afford to be courting you. And we don't know how you go on, he - he couldn't keep you, if - but anyway, after the talk, she was talking to her
 
in the kitchen, I was sat in the - in the front room. And of course after the talk she came to me and mother thought she'd come in and say, well I think I'll break it off, but she didn't, she came and put her arms round me neck and kissed me. So it made n
o
 difference. Anyway I was quite happy and - she I selected her when I was about seventeen and stuck to it. And I don't know that it's a matter of any interest but - when we had the Christian Endeavour, used to sit in the rows and we were on the back row, 
she was on a row in front. And I used to admire the shape of her ears. I might have written a poem about it had I known I was going to be poetical. She doesn't know that. I told her - told her I fell in love with her ears first.
\par }}